<HEADLINE> Singapore Pledges to Promote Women's Sport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's first national
conference on women and sport closed Tuesday after endorsing a
draft resolution calling for women's more involvement in sports.
</P>
<P>
The Women and Sport Conference 1999, themed "Women and Sport:
New Horizons", is aimed at "increasing the participation of women
and girls in sport in Singapore at all levels and in all functions
and roles, said the resolution.
</P>
<P>
"Having this conference taken place is a great achievement,"
said Kwan Yue Yeong, executive director of Singapore Sports
Council (SSC), in his closing address.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day session, SSC officials, staff of local
schools, visiting foreign scholars and students shared their
opinions of the barriers, myths and mindsets which keep women away
from sports and also discussed solutions to some of the
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Only 28 percent of women participated regularly in sports in
1997, compared with 40 percent of males, according to the result
of an SSC survey.
</P>
<P>
People at the conference agreed that family commitments, career
and even some biased social values constitute part of the
obstacles to women's participation in sports.
</P>
<P>
It is hard to follow the values of Germany, Canada and
Australia, said Kwan. "We will look for solutions that reflect
(the values) of the Chinese, the Malays and the Indians (in
Singapore)".
</P>
<P>
Some practices of Asian society can not be changed without
taking Singaporeans' interests into account, said Kwan. "We just
can't change it, no matter how fast we want to change it, no
matter how much money and resources we pour into it."
</P>
<P>
The resolution said that the principles of the Brighton
Declaration, approved at the first international conference on
women and sport in Brighton, Britain, in May 1994, should guide
actions intended to increase participation and suggest an action
plan to carry out the principles.
</P>
<P>
"We want to try to go away from here with thousands of plans
under action, let's try to get all these barriers, imbalances
corrected, and move ahead and do it in a Singaporean way that we
think is practical," said Annabel Ess, who chaired the conference
and is also an SSC member.
</P>
<P>
The situation of women's involvement in sport in Singapore "is
on the verge of becoming good", said Sue Neill, co-chair of the
International Working Group on Women and Sport and also a keynote
speaker at the conference.
</P>
<P>
Sue said that Singapore will gain much momentum to improve
women's participation in sports after the conference.
</P>
<P>
The Brighton Declaration principles include women's equity in
sport, the accessibility of facilities, school and junior sport,
leadership in sport, education, domestic and international
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The declaration's aim is to develop sports culture in a way
that enables and values the full involvement of women in every
aspect of sport.
</P>
</TEXT>
