<HEADLINE> Thailand to Start Trial of AIDS Vaccine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will start a large-scale
trial of a preventive vaccine to protect against the predominant
strain of HIV/AIDS virus found in the country, the Thai News
Agency (TNA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The trial, to be started on March 24, involves 2,500 volunteers
and is expected to provide answers to key scientific questions
within three years, TNA said.
</P>
<P>
The news agency said the volunteers would be those who were
recovered intravenous drug users from rehabilitation centers.
</P>
<P>
The trial vaccine, developed by a U.S. firm by synthetically
combining a protein, called GP120, from the outermost cover of
AIDS virus B and E strains, is one of the three "vaccine
concepts", which are being extensively explored in various
countries.
</P>
<P>
The E strain was taken from the North of Thailand to make the
vaccine in combination with the B strain which was found among
intravenous drug users in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, Jose Esparza, chief of the HIV vaccine team
of the Joint United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS, said here at an
international conference on HIV vaccine development that the
large-scale trial of the GP120 HIV vaccine in Thailand, the
world's second, and the trial in Uganda of phase I of the
so-called prime-boost vaccine will have significant meaning for
global efforts to develop an HIV vaccine in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
In addition to GP120, two more vaccines, the prime-boost
vaccine and the naked DNA vaccine made of the virus's DNA, will
undergo much larger-scale trials.
</P>
<P>
However, Esparza warned researchers to be prepared for failures
if the vaccines do not prove to be protective. 
</P>
</TEXT>
