<HEADLINE> German Government Approves Nationality Law Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN March 16 (Xinhua)--The coalition cabinet of Germany under
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder on Tuesday approved a bill to reform
the country's 86-year-old bloodlines citizenship law.
</P>
<P>
The bill will be sent to Bundestag, lower chamber of Germany's
parliament, for approval on Friday, and is expected to become law
on January 1, 2000, German Interior Minister Otto Schilly said.
</P>
<P>
Under the reform, foreign children born in Germany will
automaticly get German citizenship, and will be allowed to remain
dual-nationals until aged 23 when they will have to choose a
single nationality.
</P>
<P>
Current citizenship law of Germany, which has been effective
since year 1913, mandates that children born to foreigners in
Germany remain foreigners unless they go through a complex
naturalization process and give up their foreign passport.
</P>
<P>
The reform will allow adult foreigners in Germany to apply for
citizenship after eight years instead of the current 15-year
waiting period. Applicants will be judged on allegiance to the
German constitution, ability to speak German and a clean criminal
record.
</P>
<P>
Dual-nationality will be barred except for foreigners who have
lived longer than 30 years in Germany or are aged over 60.
</P>
<P>
Schilly ruled out the possibility of a more sweeping reform in
current legislature period, which will end in year 2002.
</P>
<P>
The reform was approved by the Greens Party, Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder's junior coalition partner.
</P>
<P>
The Greens had originally backed a far more radical reform,
which planned to offer dual-nationality to all of the 7.4 million
foreigners living in Germany.
</P>
<P>
The current version of the bill came after Schroeder's
coalition lost the local election February in Hesse state, where
anger among Germans over the planned reform helped cause the
defeat of Schroeder's Social Democrats (SPD).
</P>
<P>
Changing the citizenship law requires approval of parliament's
upper chamber, the Bundesrat, which represents 16 federal states
of Germany.
</P>
<P>
SPD, losing control of the Bundesrat due to the defeat in
Hesse, was then forced to get compromise with the tiny Free
Democratic Party (FDP) in order to collect enough upper house
votes.
</P>
<P>
FDP governs in a coalition with SPD in Rhineland-Palatinate
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
