<HEADLINE> Death Toll in U.S. Train Derailment Rises to 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- At least 12 people were killed
and over 100 others injured as a train slammed into a truck loaded
with steel bars at a crossing in Illinois State of the United
States Monday night, said reports reaching here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The train's engines and passenger cars were scattered over the
tracks, with smoke pouring from the wreckage two hours after the
crash.
</P>
<P>
The train was bound for New Orleans from Chicago. A dispatcher
with the Bourbonnais Police Department said the collision happened
around 9:40 p.m. (local time) at a crossing 90 kilometers south of
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
The train consisted of two engines and 14 passengers cars, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
"We've removed 12 bodies," Captain Ed St. Louis of the
Bourbonnais Fire Protection District said Tuesday morning. "We
believe there to be six to eight more people."
</P>
<P>
Rescuers were focusing their search in one of the sleeper cars,
said St. Louis, adding that officials were still trying to
determine if there were 214 people on the train or 216. Eighteen
crew members were on board.
</P>
<P>
He said 196 survivors from the train had been taken to
hospitals or a local school for treatment by the Red Cross. More
than 100 were taken to hospitals and at least 11 were in critical
condition.
</P>
<P>
Authorities said 101 people were taken to hospitals in nearby
Kankakee. One was airlifted to Loyola Medical Center in suburban
Chicago. Of the injured, 11 were listed in critical condition and
at least 19 in serious condition.
</P>
<P>
They said they were investigating whether gates and lights --
which were flashing after the accident -- were working before the
collision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
