<HEADLINE> Egyptian Beduins Crossing to Israel to be Deported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Israel and Egypt will soon
solve the problem over the deportation of Egyptian Bedouins from
southern Israeli border areas, said officials of a visiting
Egyptian delegation on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Some 600 Sinai Bedouins crossed the Israeli-Egyptian border on
Sunday evening and an additional 200 came over on early Tuesday
morning to Israel to escape a tribal feud, said the Israeli Army.
</P>
<P>
The tribesmen, bundled up with sacks and blankets, were stopped
by Israeli soldiers after they breached the border region of Har
Harif near Mitzpe Ramon in southern Israel.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli army source said the tribesmen received humanitarian aid
from Israeli soldiers at makeshift encampments while waiting for a
possible evacuation order,
</P>
<P>
The tribesmen, claiming they crossed the border in an effort to
escape a feud with another clan, are seeking for asylum, said the
army source.
</P>
<P>
Israeli government officials said the issue can only be solved
with the cooperation of the Egyptian government.
</P>
<P>
Israel, as a sovereign country, will not allow people to simply
migrate in, Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani told the
Israel Army Radio on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Israel will not allow more Sinai Beduins in and the issue can
be resolved by the Egyptian authorities and Sinai Beduins
themselves, said Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The issue will not affect Israel's relationship with Egypt,
said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian ambassador to Israel Mohammed Bassiouni confirmed here
Tuesday that the Sinai Beduins came to Israel due to tribal feud,
not for political reasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
