<HEADLINE> French PM Says Resignation of EU Commission Grave Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
Tuesday described the group resignation of the European Commission
as a "grave action", but said that it answers the situation.
</P>
<P>
 "The chiefs of state and government (of EU countries) should
now coordinate themselves, especially at the summit to be held in
Berlin on March 24 and 25, so that the continuity of the
functioning of the European institutions, notably the Commission,
be assured,'' he said when answering questions at the National
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Jospin also expressed his hope that the crisis should not
undermine the negotiations among EU countries concerning the
Agenda 2000 fiscal program on the spending of EU from 2000 til
2006.
</P>
<P>
"This crisis should at least be a point of departure to go
toward more transparency and democracy in the functioning of
Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 20 members of European Commission resigned early Tuesday
morning after being accused of being plagued by favoritism and
mismanagement by a committee of five wise men investigating the
accusations on fraud against the commission members.
</P>
<P>
Former French Socialist Prime Minister Edith Cresson was
particularly finger-pointed in the report for nepotism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
