<HEADLINE> U.S. Industrial Production Shows Unexpected Strength </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Reserve reported
Tuesday that output at factories, mines and utilities rose by 0.2
percent in February, led by a jump in the production of appliances
and home electronics gear.
</P>
<P>
The Fed said the increase was better than had been expected.
Many analysts had been looking for output to be unchanged in
February just as it had been in January.
</P>
<P>
The 0.2 percent rise in industrial production was the biggest
advance since a similar 0.2 percent rise in December with strength
at factories and mines offsetting lower production at the nation's
utilities.
</P>
<P>
According to Fed's report, factory output rose by 0.2 percent,
the fifth straight monthly increase for a sector that has been
hard-hit by the Asian financial crisis, which has cut into
overseas export sales and led to increased competition from
foreign imports. For February, output of consumer durable goods
rose 0.9 percent, led by large increases in the production of
appliances and home electronics. But auto production dipped a
slight 0.1 percent after a strong January increase.
</P>
<P>
Output in the mining industry was up 0.4 percent as gains in
coal mining offset weakness in oil and gas drilling. Output at the
nation's utilities was down 0.6 percent, reflecting a
warmer-than-usual February.
</P>
<P>
The nation's factories operated at 80.3 percent of capacity in
February, down slightly from January. The operating rate is the
lowest it has been since August 1992. The absence of production
bottlenecks is one reason inflation has remained well behaved.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
