<HEADLINE> International Probe for Car Bomb in N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's chief of police
Sir Ronnie Flanagan ordered on Tuesday an unprecedented
international investigation into the car bomb murder of solicitor
Rosemary Nelson.
</P>
<P>
Flanagan, head of the Royal Ulster Constabulary, appointed Kent
Chief Constable David Phillips, 54, to head the inquiry and an
Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) agent from the U.S. is also
flying in on Wednesday to join the probe.
</P>
<P>
Nelson, a prominent human rights lawyer in the province, died
on Monday after a bomb destroyed her car in Lurgan, Co Armagh, 50
km southwest of Belfast. A Protestant paramilitary group, the Red
Hand Defenders, later claimed the responsibility for the bombing.
</P>
<P>
Flanagan told BBC Radio Ulster he hoped the FBI's reputation
would provide "an international dimension as well as added
independence".
</P>
<P>
He voiced concern over the improved capability of the bombers,
the dissident loyalist Red Hand Defenders, saying the group had
not previously demonstrated the "same ruthless capability".
</P>
</TEXT>
