<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN-EU Foreign Ministers' Meeting Canceled: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Foreign Minister
Syed Hamid Albar said Tuesday the ASEAN-European Union foreign
ministers' meeting scheduled to be held in Berlin on March 30 has
been canceled.
</P>
<P>
The cancellation was agreed upon by all the nine ASEAN members,
Syed said without giving the reasons for the cancellation,
according to the Malaysian national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
The EU is said to be against Myanmar's participation in the
meeting because of its human rights record.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid was quoted as saying "(They) cannot ignore any ASEAN
country and if they (EU) don't want to give any facilities to any
ASEAN country to attend the meeting, we will definitely not attend
the meeting. This is our common stand and in that case there will
not be any meeting of foreign ministers between ASEAN and EU."
</P>
<P>
He said the issue was about a meeting between organizations and
not about the human rights practice of an ASEAN member.
</P>
<P>
He said the EU's reluctance to pursue with the meeting would
not help efforts at cooperation between the two organizations.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM) involving
ASEAN, Japan, South Korea and China which is scheduled for March
28-29 in Berlin would go on.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN comprises Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
