<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Former Liberation Army to disband </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 16 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Azanian
People's Liberation Army (APLA), which has played a role in the
struggle against the apartheid regime, is to be disbanded
Saturday, it was announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Pan Africanist Congress (PAC), of which APLA is the armed
wing, said disbanding APLA would speed up the integration process
of the South African National Defense Force (SANDF) and help
achieve real unity among former liberation fighters and government
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
A former member of the APLA high command and now a South
African navy admiral, Mosoeu Magalefa, said 10,000 former APLA
soldiers were expected to take part in a parade Saturday in Umtata
to mark the disbandment, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Although APLA abandoned the armed struggle in 1993, its
existence created an untenable situation for former members who
had since been integrated into the national defense force,
Magalefa said.
</P>
<P>
Umkhonto we Sizwe (MK), former armed wing of the African
National Congress (ANC), was disbanded in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Magalefa, a member of the SANDF's integration committee, said
the defense force was still fragmented with people being labelled
ex-APLA, ex- MK or ex-South African Defense Force members.
</P>
<P>
"It is time for us to remove misgivings or suspicions among our
 colleagues in the SANDF," Magalefa said. "We as members of APLA
can no longer be seen as people with a split loyalty."
</P>
<P>
He said a cut-off date should be announced for members of
former armed forces to join the national defense force, allowing
it to concentrate on other issues such as transformation.
</P>
<P>
APLA was formed as Poqo in 1961, shortly after the 1960
Sharpeville massacre, when police shot dead 67 people protesting
against the former government's pass laws.
</P>
<P>
Its head office was based in Tanzania. Soldiers received
training in countries such as Libya, Egypt and Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Inflation Hits Record 50 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's February year-on-year
inflation has hit an all time high of 50 percent since August 1992
when a level of 49. 1 percent was recorded, the Central
Statistical Office (CSO) said in its latest review of price trends
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This was a 5.8 percentage points increase from 44.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) stood at 859.8 in February,
representing an increase of 9.4 percent on the January level of
785.7.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990 the highest peak reached was in August 1992 of 49.1
percent followed by 46.9 percent in September of that year.
</P>
<P>
The lowest inflation was in November 1996 at 13.9 percent and
throughout in the 90s Zimbabwe's inflation had never fallen below
the two digit level.
</P>
<P>
Of the 50 percent inflation rate in February, increases in food
prices accounted for 27 percentage points while non-food items in
the CPI accounted for 23 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
Independent economist John Robertson said there was no need to
expect anything better in view of the current poor performance of
the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
