<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Low Yields Expected in Zimbabwe This year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's crop yields for the
1998/99 agricultural season will be below the expected level
because of various problems resulting from the above normal rains,
the Zimbabwean Farmers Union (ZFU) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
ZFU Director Kudakwashe Matekaire told the Zimbabwe News Agency
Ziana that the yields for the maize crop would be well above a
million tons.  Last year's maize crop reached 1.4 million tons.
</P>
<P>
He said the maize crop in most parts of the country suffered
heavily from water logging and leaching while in some dry areas it
was drought stressed.
</P>
<P>
The cotton crop, he said, suffered because pesticides were
washed way.
</P>
<P>
Cotton was a sunshine crop and most of the time it was overcast
and this reduced the cotton balls, he said.
</P>
<P>
The failure to secure loans from banks and the Agricultural
Finance Corporation would contribute to the low yields expected
this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that livestock was also affected although there was a
lot of grass. The grass which suffered from leaching lacked the
required nutrients.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe this year received above normal rains due to the La
Nina phenomenon, the persistent cooling of the sea temperatures
over the tropical Pacific Ocean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
