<HEADLINE> Nigeria Begins to Assess External Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has begun a
process of determining the nation's actual external indebtedness
as Nigeria and the Brettonwood institutions have disagreement over
t he debt profile.
</P>
<P>
The government of Nigeria has in this year's budget put the
nation's external debt profile at 28 billion U.S. dollars, but the
World Bank continued to insist on a higher figure, media reports
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted an official at the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) based in Lagos as saying Monday that "no one can say
how much the country is owing."
</P>
<P>
Neither the IMF and the World Bank, nor the Nigerian government
can say what the country owed its external creditors, IMF acting
Chief Public Affairs Official Bruno Mauprivez added.
</P>
<P>
IMF's African Department official Brian Ames noted that Nigeria
has not been able to manage the compilation of its external debt
profile properly.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the problem to the movement of government
departments from Lagos to Abuja and lack of adequate and efficient
computerization system.
</P>
<P>
In conjunction with the Department for International
Development, a British agency, Nigeria is currently making efforts
to reconcile the actual external debt figure.
</P>
<P>
It was learnt that the on-going reconciliation of the debt
profile would be completed by July this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
