<HEADLINE> Canada to increase Emergency Food Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Canada announced Tuesday that
Canada, through the Canadian International Development Agency
(CIDA), will increase its emergency food aid package to respond to
extraordinary food relief requests.
</P>
<P>
The new food aid package, totalling 29 million Canadian dollars
(19 million U.S. dollars), is expected to reach over 850,000
people, around the world, who are in emergency situations, said a
news release.
</P>
<P>
"The increase in the number of natural disasters and civil
conflicts around the world last year, coupled with the increase in
the numbers of people affected, has placed an enormous strain on
the ability of many developing countries to provide enough food to
feed their people," said Canadian International Cooperation
Minister Diane Marleau in the release.
</P>
<P>
"In response to the magnitude of the emergencies, CIDA is
allocating new money to used primarily to support major emergency
food aid operations, world-wide," added the minister.
</P>
<P>
The new food aid package will be used by Canadian
non-governmental organization and the United Nations to buy
foodstuff. For example, 3 million Canadian dollars (1.98 million
U.S. dollars) will go to aid programs in Central American
countries affected by Hurricane Mitch. The storm destroyed most of
the crops and left thousands homeless in the affected countries of
the region. Emergency relief efforts in other countries, including
Ethiopia, China, Afghanistan, and Indonesia, will also benefit
from this aid package.
</P>
<P>
Approximately one-half of the food commodities purchased under
this initiative will be in the form of Canadian wheat. Other
Canadian foods, such as pulses and edible oil, will make up the
majority of the balance.
</P>
<P>
This initiative will have a spin-off benefit of generating new
sales for Canadian food producers, who are facing economic
difficulties in the current environment of low international
commodity prices, said the release.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
