<HEADLINE> Rebels Kill 210 Kabila's Fighters in Southeast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Congolese rebels fighting to oust
 president Laurent Kabila from power claimed that they had killed
210 of Kabila's fighters, including 80 Zimbabweans in clashes near
Kabinda town Monday, the Rwanda News Agency (RNA) reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
''Those killed included the Zimbabwean area commander in Kabinda
zone,'' one rebel commander, based in Kisangani, the third
largest city of former Zaire, was quoted as sayingTuesday.
</P>
<P>
The fighting broke out at dawn when Kabila's forces and allies
tried to launch an assault on the Lubao Front, said the commander,
which RNA did not give his name.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, now advancing toward Kabinda, 150 km east of
mineral-rich Mbuji-Mayi town in eastern Kasai Province, also
claimed they had captured two tanks, two armored personnel
carriers and taken four prisoners of war during the fighting.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Rwandan ministry of defense predicted that
 Kabinda is about to fall in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The rebels are backed by Rwanda and Uganda, while Zimbabwe,
Namibia, Angola and Chad, as well as regional guerrilla forces are
supporting Kabila in the seven-month old civil war.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to broker a peace deal in the conflict have failed to
materialize because Kabila continued to refuse to engage in direct
talks with the rebels, alleging that he is faced with foreign
aggression. 
</P>
