<HEADLINE> Contact Group Rejects Serb Request for Amendment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The six-nation Contact Group on
former Yugoslavia rejected on Tuesday a request by the Serbs for
substantial amendments to be made in the draft peace agreement on
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman of the Contact Group countries -- the United
States, Russia, France, Britain, Germany and Italy -- said that
many changes as are demanded by the Yugoslav delegation concern
some fundamental elements which have already been agreed upon
during the Rambouillet talks three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
``The changes... would jeopardize the key elements of the
agreements of Rambouillet,'' said the spokesmen in a statement.
</P>
<P>
They said that the Yugoslav delegation was told that only
technical adjustments could be considered for the political wing
of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav delegation presented Monday evening a request for
substantial amendments to be made in the political part of the
agreement on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Both the Yugoslav side and the Kosovo Albanians accepted in
principle the political part of the agreement during the
Rambouillet talks.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian delegates said on Monday that they would sign the
agreement, which calls for substantial autonomy of Kosovo and the
disarming of the separatist force the Kosovo Liberation Army
(KLA).
</P>
<P>
But the Yugoslav side remains firm in its rejection of the
deployment of a NATO-led force in Kosovo to guarantee the
implementation of the agreement. 
</P>
