<HEADLINE> Egypt to Modernize Industry in Cooperation with EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has planned to modernize its
industry in cooperation with the European Union (EU), the
country's Middle East News Agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The modernization program to upgrade 5,000 industrial firms
across Egypt is estimated to cost 827 million euros (909.7 million
U.S. dollars), Egyptian Minister of Industry Suleiman Reda told a
symposium late Monday.
</P>
<P>
The EU will offer Egypt 650 million euros (715 million dollars)
in grants and loans for the project, Reda said. The Egyptian
government and the private sector will cover the rest of the cost,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Experts from Portugal, France and Spain will help the Egyptian
enterprises to carry out the program, Reda said.
</P>
<P>
The renovation and development program will enable the Egyptian
industry to open new markets for export and withstand the
challenges prompted by globalization, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The plan will be referred to the People's Assembly (parliament)
for approval early next month and a relevant agreement will be
concluded with the EU in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
