<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Calls for Urgent Funds to Feed 1 Million Tanzanians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. World Food
Program (WFP) has appealed to donors for contributions to feed
over a million Tanzanians suffering from severe food shortages.
</P>
<P>
Due to serious crop failures in Tanzania, WFP said over the
weekend that it needs to begin distributing food immediately to
1.4 million people living in 12 regions of the East African
country.
</P>
<P>
However, a recent appeal to donors for 20,000 metric tons of
food aid valued at about 8 million U.S. dollars raised only half
that amount.
</P>
<P>
According to WFP's country director for Tanzania Irene Lacy, if
the agency did not get additional funds to mount the operation
soon, malnutrition and other hunger-related diseases might cost
human lives.
</P>
<P>
"The food aid, we're planning to distribute is the very minimum
needed to stave off a major crisis," she said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, WFP has approved a 23 million U.S.
dollars of emergency food aid program for people facing severe
food shortages in Mauritania, Senegal, Gambia and Cape Verde.
</P>
<P>
The six-month operation will provide food to more than one
million people living in areas affected by drought and
below-average harvests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
