<HEADLINE> S. Africa Airlifts Food to Flood-Stricken Mozambique  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This is the last batch of food relief by South Africa to
Mozambique, which has encountered the largest floods in 40 years,
media reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The relief team, which is consisted of 54 people, eight
aircraft and two helicopters, has sent 130 tons of maize, beans
and other foodstuffs to Vilanculos and Govuro counties of the
province, where tens of thousands of people are facing starvation
after roads are washed away by floods,
</P>
<P>
The chief of the team, Lionel Sacoyer, said he has completed
the relief mission and their planes are scheduled to return on
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The floods have affected more than 0.4 million people in
Mozambique, half of whom need emergency food relief. The southern
African country said it needs 12.4 million U.S. dollars of relief
fund. 
</P>
