<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Links Amino Acid to Disappearance of Rare Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- British scientists claimed Tuesday
they may have identified the reason why some children with a rare
form of brain cancer are spontaneously cured.
</P>
<P>
In the UK, every year just over 70 children develop
neuroblastoma, the tumor which can be highly dangerous and spread
to other parts of the body. But in five percent of cases, the rare
cancer mysteriously disappears.
</P>
<P>
A team of British scientists, led by Professor David Latchman
from University College London, believed the reason is that the
cancer cells spontaneously switch back to normal ones.
</P>
<P>
The scientists suggested that two molecules may play a key role
in the switch. The molecules are thought to act like traffic
lights, with one telling the tumor to convert to a normal cell and
the other telling it to remain as a cancerous cell.
</P>
<P>
The team found that the presence of just one amino acid, the
building block of proteins, can make the difference between
whether a molecule tells the tumor cell to become normal or stay
cancerous.
</P>
<P>
In laboratory tests, the scientists found that the message
given by the molecules can be changed by simply adding the amino
acid.
</P>
<P>
The team is now looking more closely at the amino acid to see
how it affects the way the molecules interact with other proteins
in the body.
</P>
<P>
Further study could lead to the development or gene therapy to
treat neuroblastoma, said the scientists.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0040 </DOCNO>
