<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Blames Gulf States for Maneuvers with U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Tuesday blamed the Gulf
states for conducting joint military exercises with the United
States and Britain in the region.
</P>
<P>
"If there is any criticism, it should go to those maneuvers
held jointly with the U.S. and Britain which have no rights in the
region," the Iranian Government Spokesman Ataollah Mohajerani
told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The criticism came one day after foreign ministers of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) issued a statement in the Saudi capital
of Riyadh, criticizing Iran for staging military maneuvers in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani, also Minister of Culture and Islamic Guidance,
said Iran considers launching its maneuvers as a natural and
indisputable right and all countries in the region are entitled to
maintain their defensive capabilities.
</P>
<P>
Iran has always tried to develop its relations with its
neighbors on the basis of mutual respect, the spokeman said, in
response to accusations from Qatar that the war games pose a
threat to the countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian navy staged a nine-day military maneuver earlier
this month near Abu Musa island, over which the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) also claims sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The GCC foreign ministers on Monday called on Iran to settle
its disputes with the UAE over the three islands of Abu Musa, the
Greater and the Lesser Tunbs near the strategic shipping lane at
the mouth of the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry Spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi on Monday
evening turned down the GCC call, saying that Tehran has the
absolute right to stage military maneuvers for defensive purposes
and to safeguard the territorial integrity of the country.
</P>
<P>
He denied the GCC's support for the UAE sovereignty over the
disputed islands, stating the three islands are an inseparable part
of the Iranian territory.
</P>
<P>
Asefi said the only way to settle the existing
"misunderstanding" between Iran and the UAE is to hold bilateral
talks.
</P>
<P>
Iran took over the islands in 1971 after the British forces
pulled out from the region. However, both Tehran and Abu Dhabi
claim sovereignty over the islands.
</P>
<P>
During the past years, Iran insisted on bilateral talks to
solve the issue, but the UAE called for an international
arbitration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
