<HEADLINE> U.N. Special Envoy Shocked by Sarajevo Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The special representative
of the U.N. secretary-general, Elisabeth Rehn, voiced her shock
and horror at the car-bomb explosion on Tuesday morning in
Sarajevo, capital of Bosnia, which injured Jozo Leutar, deputy
minister of interior of the Bosnia and Hezergovina's Moslem-Croat
federation, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
Condemning it in the strongest terms, Rehn said that whatever
the purpose of this act, it is doomed to fail. The violent actions
of a few cannot destroy the seed of peace which has firmly taken
root in Bosnia and Herzegovina, Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
The bomb went off at 06:50GMT near Leutar's home in central
Sarajevo, local police said. Two other occupants in the car
sustained lesser injuries.
</P>
<P>
Rehn expressed her appreciation of Leutar's work, particularly
with regard to his contribution to the establishment of the
Federal Ministry of Interior, and wished Leutar and his colleagues
"a full and speedy recovery," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Mission in Bosnia and Herzegovina "will not spare any
effort to support the work of the local police to ensure that the
perpetrators of this cowardly act are brought to justice," said
the special envoy.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's incident comes at a time when Bosnian Croats are
growingly complaining about their status inside the Moslem-Croat
federation, which together with the Serb republic make up post-war
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
In February, a Bosnian Croat police officer was injured in a
bomb attack in the central town of Tranik, also the scene of other
such attacks in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-brokered 1995 Dayton accord ended the 1992-1995
Bosnian war by dividing the country into the federation and the
Serb republic. 
</P>
