<HEADLINE> Arabs Back Palestinian Statehood: Moussa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said Tuesday it was a united and unbargainable Arab stand
to support the establishment of a Palestinian state with Jerusalem
as its capital.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at Jordan's southern port city of Aqaba,
where leaders of the two countries were attending an inauguration
ceremony of a joint power grid between the two states.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the ceremony, Moussa said that the
Palestinian state must be eventually established in the West Bank
and the Gaza Strip with Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
He described the setup of a Palestinian state as an important
strategic choice and a united stand of all Arab countries, which
can not be bargained.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the final status of Jerusalem would not
be subjected to policies of the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
However, Moussa apparently dodged a sensitive question whether
his country would support a plan by Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat to unilaterally declare an independent state on May 4.
</P>
<P>
The timing for establishing a Palestinian state is a "technical
issue" which can be open to discussions, he said.
</P>
<P>
The interim Oslo peace agreement between Israel and the
Palestinians expires on May 4, and Arafat is holding extensive
consultations with Arab and western countries on whether to
unilaterally declare the Palestinian state on the day.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace process has been deadlocked since
the end of 1998, with the two sides accusing each other of failing
to fulfill obligations stipulated in the latest Wye River peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, Israel should have withdrawn its troops from
another 13 percent of the West Bank while the Palestinian
authorities launched tougher actions against Islamic militants.
</P>
