Kofi Annan on Tuesday expressed his profound sadness over a U.N.
plane crash which happened in Haiti last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Annan extended his condolences to families of all the victims
during this time of sorrow.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-charted helicopter with 13 people abroad crashed on
its way to Labadie, on the north coast of Haiti, to assist a
seriously injuried person.
</P>
<P>
The MI-8 Russian helicopter was contracted with a U.S. company.
The 13 people included six Russians, six Argentines and one
American. The six Argentines were U.N. civilian police of the UN
mission in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard announced this noon that there were
no survivors in the U.N. helicopter crash.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard said a search team from the U.N. mission in Haiti
arrived at the site of the crash late yesterday and searched the
area this morning.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard said most of the bodies are burned beyond recognition
and the U.N. team was planning to bring back the bodies to the
capital of Haiti by the end of today.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations had sent an air safety expert to join the
investigation of crash, Eckhard added.
</P>
<P>
The crash represented the worst loss of life yet during the
United Nations mission.  
</P>
