<HEADLINE> Three Deals Signed for Oil Prospection in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Egypt on Tuesday signed three
agreements with foreign companies in off-shore oil prospection in
the Mediterranean Sea.
</P>
<P>
Under a deal signed with Shell, Egypt offered a concession to
the multinational oil company in an area of 41,500 square
kilometers in the Mediterranean northwest of Egypt, the country's
Middle East News Agency (MENA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Shell will invest a minimum of 230 million U.S. dollars in
prospection and drill 10 exploratory wells, MENA said.
</P>
<P>
A second agreement allows the Italian international company Eni
to carry out oil prospection in a 919-square-kilometer area north
of Bardawil, 190 kilometers northeast of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The company is to spend 60 million dollars in oil prospection
and drill nine wells.
</P>
<P>
The third deal is an amendment to an agreement with Amoco,
under which the United States company will spend 450 million
dollars and drill nine wells.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Petroleum Hamdi el-Banbi said after the
signing ceremony that the investments of foreign companies in oil
prospection in Egypt have not been affected by the low-level oil
prices in the world markets.
</P>
<P>
Foreign oil companies have not reduced investments in Egypt,
instead, a number of them have increased investments and intend to
expand their activities, el-Banbi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
