<HEADLINE> No Large Military Operation on Iraq: U.S. General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. General
Anthony Zinni, Commander of U.S. forces in Gulf, dismissed on
Tuesday speculations that Washington is planning to launch
large-scale military operations against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British aircraft "are currently implementing United
Nations resolutions concerning the no-fly zones in north and south
Iraq," Zinni said in an interview with Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Defending the recurrent U.S.-led strikes against Iraqi targets
inside the no-fly zones, Zinni said "all the strikes that have
been carried out by our planes are in self defense."
</P>
<P>
"These strikes could stop at any time provided that the Iraqi
regime refrains from striking out aircraft," said the general, who
returned from a tour of U.S. troops stationed at Kuwait's Doha
Camp, about 60 kilometers north of the capital.
</P>
<P>
General Zinni arrived in Kuwait Monday for a two-day visit as
part of a regional tour that has taken him to Egypt and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
He also stopped Sunday at the international defense
exhibition, the region's largest arms show, in the United Arab
Emirates.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his visit to Doha Camp, the U.S. general held talks
with Kuwaiti Prime Minister Crown Prince Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Sabah
and Kuwaiti Defense Minister Salem Al-Sabah, the local television
station reported. But the TV reports didn't mention details of the
meetings.
</P>
<P>
There are about 4,000 U.S. troops based in Kuwait, with some
commissioned with safeguarding pre-positioned weapons and others
with conducting joint exercises with Kuwaiti armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait signed a 10-year defense cooperation pact with the
United States following the 1991 Gulf War that ended Iraq's
seven-month occupation of the oil-rich Gulf state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
