<HEADLINE> Angola, IMF Talks in Positive Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Sources from the visiting
International Monetary Fund (IMF) delegation said here Tuesday its
negotiations with the Angolan government on the new economy
monitoring program are in "positive" progress.
</P>
<P>
Paulo Newhouse, head of the IMF delegation which arrived here
last Friday, said the implementation of the program projected at
monitoring government financial expenditure is the prerequisite
for Angola to obtain loans from the organization.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 national budget of Angola will be tabled to parliament
for approval at the end of this month and the IMF delegation will
evaluate the government's revenue and public payment policies,
according to Newhouse.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the IMF required the Angolan government to strictly
restrict its financial spending, lower inflation rate, be
transparent about its accounting, eliminate gradually government
control on foreign exchange, and implement the enhanced structural
adjustment facility as conditions for getting its low-interest
loans.
</P>
<P>
Due to the renewal of fighting between the Angolan government
and the rebel National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA) which has plunged the peace process into crisis, the
economy monitoring program failed to be implemented.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that the serious deficit in Angola's
finance will hardly be averted given the escalating military
expenditure and increasing refugees which now recorded at over 20
million. Therefore, it is difficult for the IMF and the Angolan
government to reach an agreement on the new economy monitoring
program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
