<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Work on Eradicating Tsetse Flies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Science and Technology
Commission of Ethiopia announced here Tuesday that a laboratory
which will experiment with methods to eradicate tsetse flies,
vector of trypanosomiosis, will soon be set up in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian News Agency quoted Assefa Mebrate, coordinator of
the South Ethiopia Rift Valley Tsetse Fly Eradication Project, as
saying that the laboratory will alter the genetic make up of the
flies to stop them from multiplying.
</P>
<P>
The laboratory will be established at Kaliti, in the suburbs of
capital Addis Ababa to serve as a central supply of the altered
tsetse flies to affected areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia loses millions of dollars annually as a result of
trypanosomiosis which "is taking a heavy toll on its cattle
resources", said the coordinator.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that ten million of the 30 million head of
cattle in Ethiopia are found in tsetse fly infested regions
covering about 200,000 square km of land. The southwestern and
northwestern parts of the country are rife with the tsetse flies.
</P>
</TEXT>
