<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, US at Odds Over Common Agriculture Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Commissioner for
agriculture, Franz Fischler, said here Tuesday that the European
Union (EU) has carried out the most radical reform on its common
agriculture policy (CAP) and made substantial changes in farm
expenditure, hardly no one could describe the changes as "status
quo".
</P>
<P>
He was responding to remarks by the US Agriculture Secretary
Glickman that the EU's reform agreement on CAP made last week is
"not much more than maintaining the status quo".
</P>
<P>
Describing the US comment as "incredible and regrettable",
Fischler said it would been wiser had Mr. Glickman taken some time
to study and analyze the agreement in detail before drawing
conclusions. "Had he done so, he would have appreciated that this
is the most radical reform ever carried out in the history of the
CAP."
</P>
<P>
The commissioner said the United States always had difficult
understanding of the philosophy underlying the CAP and of the
attachment the EU governments and citizens have to ensuring the
protection of Europe's rural heritage.
</P>
<P>
"It is unfortunate that the many years of discussions and
clarifications do not seem to have led to any greater appreciation
on their part," Fischler added.
</P>
<P>
It is to be clear, Fischler said in a statement, that the EU
and US share many common interests on agriculture, it is equally
clear that we have important differences in terms of the
objectives of our respective agricultural policies. "There is no
reason why both policies cannot coexist in a non conflictual way."
</P>
<P>
He also told his US partners that the multifunctional aspect of
the EU's agriculture policy is not for negotiation and EU has no
intention of sacrifying it on the "altar of free trade". Fischler
pointed out that the outcome of Agenda 2000, the EU's reform
program, is not an opening bid in the WTO discussions foreseen but
rather the policy with which any future WTO agreement must be
fully compatible.
</P>
<P>
Finally he said that rather than permanently attacking the CAP,
the US should perhaps examine their own policies which provide
substantially more assistance per US farmer than the CAP does for
EU farmers, but in less transparent way and for less of a return
to society.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, it should be recognized that far from being a
"fortress-Europe", the EU is the largest importer of food and
agricultural products in the world, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
