<HEADLINE> Security Council Underlines Monitoring of Arms Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
on Tuesday attached great importance to the effective
international monitoring of the arms embargo against Yugoslavia
under the Security Council Resolution 1160, adopted in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press, the president of the
15-member Council, Qin Huasun of China, said that "members of the
Council reiterate the importance of effective international
monitoring of the arms embargo established by Council Resolution
1160."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council members "remind all States of the need to
strictly implement arms embargo and to submit to the Committee the
necessary information on violations of the embargo," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Security Council endorse the report of the
Sanctions Committee," and "express their gratitude to the
Committee and its Chairman for their work," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council reiterate their full support of the
enhancement of effectiveness of the Committee and express their
intention to follow its activities closely," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council adopted Resolution 1160 on March 31, 1999,
deciding to impose arms embargo on the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia. China, one of the five permanent members of the
Security Council, abstained from the voting. 
</P>
