<HEADLINE> Nigeria Moves to Solve Grievances in Niger Delta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A special committee set up by the
Nigerian government Tuesday presented a report to Nigeria's Head
of State General Abdulsalami Abubakar, advocating a 20-year master
plan for the development of Niger Delta.
</P>
<P>
Oladayo Popoola, chairman of the 22-member committee charged
with evolving short and long term development options for the
area, said here Tuesday that a development council would be set up
for the area to coordinate various development projects.
</P>
<P>
The report presented by the committee proposed that rural
electrification projects for the area estimated at 1.7 billion
naira (about 20 million U.S. dollars) should be completed before
the handover of power on May 29.
</P>
<P>
Another 15.3 billion naira (about 178 million dollars) should
be made available to address the urgent infrastructural needs of
the area "to enable an immediate impact to be felt during the life
of this administration", the report said.
</P>
<P>
Two technical colleges should be built in Delta and Bayelsa
states in a bid to contribute to the development of the skills of
the youths of the area.
</P>
<P>
Popoola said, "The Niger Delta has the highest concentration of
 commerecial investments financed with public funds in the country
today."
</P>
<P>
He cited such investments as two refineries, a petrochemical
and a power plant in Rivers State, an aluminium smelting and a
newsprint plant in Cross Rivers State and a steel plant and a
power station in Delta State.
</P>
<P>
In spite of such investments, Popoola said, a combination of
difficult geographical terrain, the scaterred nature of
settlements, historical competition and mistrust among the ethnic
groups in the area have served to undermine the realization of
government objectives.
</P>
<P>
The Niger Delta area has been the scene of recent violent
demonstrations by Ijaw youths who were involved in intermittent
disruption of oil production activities, the mainstay of the
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The lack of infrastructure and training of the youths are often
 criticized by Ijaw youths who have always alleged marginalization
of the Niger Delta in the West African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
