<HEADLINE> Mcdonald Offers to Resign as ICTY Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Gabrielle Kirk Mcdonald,
president of the International Criminal Tribunal for the Former
Yugoslavia (ICTY), has tendered her resignation effective in
November 1999, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the reasons for her resignation, the U.N. spokesman
said that she had served two terms already, "and it's purely for
personal reasons that she would like to come home."
</P>
<P>
In a letter distributed to her staff Tuesday, she wrote, "I
will continue to support the work of the Tribunal in any way that
I can. I am sure each of you is as proud as I am to be part of
this historical development of international humanitarian law,
which the Tribunal represents."
</P>
<P>
"I sincerely appreciate the opportunity to have been a fellow
participant in the accomplishment of the Tribunal," the letter
said.
</P>
<P>
Mcdonald has failed in its repeated efforts to ask the U.N.
Security Council to impose one-sided pressure on Belgrade since
the breakout of the Kosovo crisis in February last year.
</P>
<P>
Some Security Council members have accused of the ICTY of being
used as a political tool on the issue of Kosovo, a province in the
Yugoslav Republic of Serbia, which constitutes the violation of
internal affairs of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
A native of the United States, Judge Mcdonald was elected by
the United Nations General Assembly as a Judge of the ICTY in
September 1993 and re-elected on May 20, 1997 for a second
four-year term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
