<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Envoy: No Foreign Military Presence in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Ambassador to Russia
Borislav Milosevic said here Tuesday that Belgrade accepts no
military presence from any foreign country, even that of friendly
Russia.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat said the current talks on Kosovo in France might
be crowned by a political agreement if the sides "show flexibility
and determination to sign not a unilateral, but a mutually
acceptable document envisaging a real autonomy and providing for
no force scenarios," Itar-Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
"It is inadmissible to insist on unilateral concessions from
Belgrade, but if Albanians want autonomy they will have it,"
Milosevic said.
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed to a broad autonomy, but we cannot accept
Kosovo's Serb population becoming national minority," he added.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said it is possible that head of the would-be
Kosovo autonomy might be called president but it is "imperative to
specify the sphere of his competence which must not go outside the
framework of Serbia's constitution."
</P>
<P>
Kosovo is a region within Yugoslavia's Serbia Republic.
</P>
<P>
He expressed concern that certain U.S. and NATO military
circles are bent on sending combat units to Kosovo, a move which
targets to "reinforce NATO's southern flank."
</P>
<P>
Milosevic vowed that Belgrade will defend itself "by all means
available" in the event of foreign troops introduction to Kosovo,
Tass said.
</P>
<P>
However, the ambassador said he hopes that "all the talk about
possible force solution to the Kosovo problem is of tactical
character, and the world community will not allow military
interference into domestic affairs of a sovereign state." 
</P>
</TEXT>
