<HEADLINE> DPRK Agrees to U.S. Access to Kumchang-ri Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Pyongyang Tuesday agreed to
Washington access to an underground site at Kumchang-ri with the
latter promising to improve bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached after lengthy talks between the two
countries with the latest in New York from February 27 to March
15, according to a DPRK-U.S. joint press statement issued here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The United States and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
(DPRK) believe that "successful cooperation to remove U.S.
concerns about an underground site at Kumchang-ri will contribute
to improved relations between the two countries," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The text was read by U.S. Special Envoy Charles Kartman who
headed the U.S. delegation. Sitting by his side at a press
conference at the U.S. Mission to the United Nations was DPRK
delegation head Vice Foreign Minister Kim Gye Gwan.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK will provide the U.S. with "satisfactory access" to
the site "by inviting a U.S. delegation for an initial visit in
May 1999 and allowing additional visits to remove U.S. concerns
about the site's future use," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. has decided to take a step to improve political and
economic relations between the two countries," it added.
</P>
<P>
Both Kartman and Kim did not elaborate plans on the development
of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
A statement by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
released at the press conference said the U.S. has decided to take
"a concrete step in the form of a bilateral pilot agricultural
project."
</P>
<P>
However, Albright said the U.S. "did not agree to North Korean
demands for compensation" in return for access to the site.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said Washington has suspicions that the
Kimchang-ri site "may be part of a clandestine nuclear weapons
program." Pyongyang has denied it and asked the U.S. to compensate
if the site is not as what it was suspected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
