<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Cracks Down on Parks Poachers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian federal government
has introduced legislation to dramatically increase fines and jail
terms for poachers who hunt species like grizzlies in Canada's
national parks.
</P>
<P>
The new National Park Act, tabled Tuesday at the House of
Commons, allows judges to send poachers to prison for up to five
years, instead of what the current legislation calls for -- a
maximum jail term of six months.
</P>
<P>
Poachers could be fined 150,000 Canadian dollars (99,000 U.S.
dollars) for hunting or possessing "threatened" wildlife under the
act.
</P>
<P>
If enacted, the toughest penalties will be imposed on hunters
who poach or traffic endangered and threatened species like
mountain goats, grizzlies, bighorn sheep, peregrine falcons, polar
bears, or piping plover.
</P>
<P>
And the penalties for the lesser offense of hunting "protected
" species like American buffalo, American elk, caribou, cougars,
moose wolves, black bears, and white-tailed deer in national parks
are also going up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
