<HEADLINE> Britain Favors G8 to Contribute to Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Britain supports leaders of the
Group of Eight (G8) countries to join hands in finding a solution
to the Cyprus issue, said British High Commissioner to Cyprus
David Madden on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting with Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides,
Madden said both Britain and the U.S. intend to join in
"a continuing and very full international efforts to assist a
settlement."
</P>
<P>
Referring to reports that a senior U.S. official is working on
getting the G8 countries engaged in the Cyprus peace effort,
Madden said it should be seen "as part of continuing international
efforts to help and assist the parties here to come to a solution".
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the island
in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island,
but so far no tangible results have been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Madden is to leave Cyprus at the end of the month and in early
May he is due in Athens to take up the post of British Ambassador
to Greece.
</P>
<P>
The G8 countries include the United States, Germany, France,
Italy, Canada, Japan, Russia and Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
