<HEADLINE> U.S. Nation's Delinquency Rate on Mortgages Falls Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. nation's mortgage-
delinquency rate fell to its lowest level in more than two years
during the fourth quarter of 1998 as a strong economy and low
mortgage rates kept U.S. residents current with their housing
bills, the Wall Street Journal reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Mortgage Bankers Association of America said the nation's
delinquency rate fell to 4.24 percent from 4.37 percent for the
third quarter and stands at its lowest level since the third
quarter of 1996. The mortgage bankers' survey covers mortgage
loans on one-unit to four-unit residential properties and includes
about half of U.S. residential mortgages.
</P>
<P>
The group attributed the drop to a strong economy, which has
ensured low unemployment. Low mortgage rates have increased home
buying and refinancing, and the group noted that new mortgages
typically see fewer delinquency problems. Low rates encouraged
borrowers to take out fixed-rate mortgages instead of less-stable
adjustable-rate mortgages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Still Faces Financial Difficulties, Officials Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations is
still facing financial difficulties despite the improvement in the
cash flow, U.N. officials said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis, which has long haunted the world body,
originated from the U.S. reluctance to pay its back dues.
</P>
<P>
The United States still owed 76 percent of all unpaid regular
budget assessments at the end of 1998, said Joseph Connor, the
U.N. under-secretary-general in charge of finance and budget. At
present, the United States owed 1.7 billion U.S. dollars of its
back dues.
</P>
<P>
"We have no capital, we have no reserves, we borrow form some
Member States to make up for the income we do not get from other
Member States," Connor said.
</P>
<P>
Connor told a meeting of the Administrative and Budgetary
Committee, also known as the Fifth Committee of the General
Assembly, that for the first time in four years, the Organization
was borrowing less from peacekeeping funds to cover regular budget
activities, and cash balances were higher.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the level of unpaid regular budget assessments was
decreasing substantially, Connor said.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, unpaid regular budget assessments had been 564 million
U.S. dollars while at the end of 1998, they came to 417 million
U.S. dollars and the deficit in the regular budget cash was down.
</P>
<P>
Many Member States, including some of its Western allies, have
frequently lashed out at Washington for its reluctance to pay its
back dues, repeatedly urging the United States to fulfill its
obligations under the U.N. Charter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
