<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF, Angola Talks Make Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) said Wednesday that its talks with the government of Angola
on implementing an economic monitoring program have made "positive
progress."
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made by leader of an IMF delegation in Angola,
Paulo Newhuose, who said here that implementation of the program
is a precondition for IMF to extend loans to Angola.
</P>
<P>
Newhuose arrived in the Angolan capital of Luanda last Friday.
He said Angola's ministries of finance and planning have showed
the utmost respect for IMF's assessment of the current situation
in the country and for its opinions on how Angola should proceed
in the present fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Newhuose, who is also in charge of IMF's African and Middle
East Affairs, said that although the present work remains to be
technical, it may produce far-reaching impact on future
agreements.
</P>
<P>
He said Angola's 1999 state budget proposals will be submitted
to parliament for approval at the end of this month, and that the
IMF delegation will evaluate the government policies on income and
public expenditure before making any suggestions.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the IMF worked out with the Angolan government a
similar program focusing on the stern control of the government
expenditure, curbing inflation, making the state account
transparent, and lifting of the government control over foreign
exchange step by step.
</P>
<P>
Another precondition for the IMF to extend loans to Angola is
smooth implementation of the economic monitoring program, which
means satisfying the terms of the Enhanced Structural Adjustment
Facility (ESAF).
</P>
<P>
ESAF is a favorable treatment given by the IMF to low-income
countries which are undergoing economic restructuring programs.
The ESAF loans are granted at a rate as low as 0.5 percent with a
long repayment period.
</P>
<P>
However, the eruption of the civil war in Angola again has
stalled the implementation of the monitoring program.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said it will be difficult for IMF to smoothly
reach an agreement with Angola on implementing a new economic
monitoring program as the civil war has forced the military
spending to shoot up and refugees to rise to more than 20 million.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
