<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Forensic Team Establishes No Massacre Case for Racak Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRISTINA, Kosovo, Yugoslavia, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Finnish
forensic team, sent in by the European Union, did not establish a
case of massacre for the Racak incident, in which 40 people died
last January 15.
</P>
<P>
A conclusion of "massacre" did not fall within the competence
of the EU forensic team or any other person having participated
solely in the investigation of the bodies, read a summary given by
Helena Ranta, chief of the forensic team.
</P>
<P>
The Finnish woman pathologist told the press after handing over
the team's autopsy findings on the 40 bodies of local civilians to
the local Pristina district court and that Energy Dispersive X-Ray
Analyzer tests proved them to be unarmed.
</P>
<P>
Of the 40 bodies autopsied at Pristina, there was one woman and
several elderly men.
</P>
<P>
Previous western press reports claimed that there were 45
bodies including two women and one child, while the Kosovo cease-
fire verification mission of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe said that there were 41 bodies including
those of two women and one child.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the gunshot residue analyses, the Finnish forensic
team also confirmed that the dead people were civilians, for no
ammunition was found in their pockets.
</P>
<P>
"It is highly unlikely that clothes could have been changed or
removed," read the summary of the forensic investigation which
added that "no indication of tampering or fabrication of evidence
was detected".
</P>
<P>
The Finnish scientist only complained about the fact that 16
bodies had been autopsied before the pathologists from Finland,
Yugoslavia and Belarussia joined together. "It was against the
wish of our pathologists, " the summary said.
</P>
<P>
But the team admitted that all pathologists agreed upon common
methods and procedures after a demonstration autopsy and local
criminal and autopsy technicians contributed to the cooperative
working atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
"The Finnish team was able to complete its investigations
without any outside pressure," said Ranta.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav and Belarussian pathologists had earlier
established no case of massacre last month but the Finnish team
reserved its announcement only until after it had completed its
investigation.
</P>
<P>
"In Finland, ongoing investigations are not commented upon,"
said Ranta.
</P>
<P>
When asked why it took almost two months for her team to
announce its findings, Ranta said that the investigation was
complicated and it only completed a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
No sooner had the bodies been found close to Racak, a village
south to the Kosovo provincial capital of Pristina, William Walker,
head of the Kosovo Verification Mission alleged that it was a
massacre.
</P>
<P>
The Finnish pathologists said that laymen with little criminal
investigation knowledge may tend to interpret what they saw at the
site of the tragedy at Racak as massacre.
</P>
<P>
Ranta explained that the missing eyes and ears could be related
to animal activities such as stray dogs or to the high pressure of
projectiles.
</P>
<P>
The Finnish pathologist said that now it is up to the local law
enforcement authorities to piece together all evidence to
establish a criminal case.
</P>
<P>
However, Ranta emphasized that so many people died at "
approximately the same time" was a crime against humanity and she
appealed to the international community to continue what it has
been doing to help stop such crime in Kosovo, where so far some 2,
000 people died in armed conflicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
