<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Seeks Trial of Rwandan Genocide Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He said that as the second choice, Natuyahaga should be handed
over to the Tanzanian authorities and then be extradited to
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Belgium's demand was put forward following the bid by the
Natuyahaga's prosecutor to seek withdrawing indictment against
him.
</P>
<P>
In the unprecedented application, Othman Chande argued that the
 withdrawal will promote the exercise of concurrent jurisdiction
by a state as contained in Article 8 of the Statute of the
tribunal.
</P>
<P>
He said that the accused on a single count indictment would not
fit into the prosecution's current strategy of showing the
genocide as a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
He argued that the Belgian government has already investigated
the case and the families of the victims are also in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian investigating magistrate issued in 1995 an
international warrant of arrest of Natuyahaga, accusing him of
involving in the death of 10 Belgian peace keeping soldiers in the
United Nations Assistance Mission in Rwanda (UNAMIR) on April 7,
1994 as well as former Rwandan Prime Minister Agathe
Uwilingiyimana.
</P>
<P>
However, Natuyahaga's defense counsel Georges Amegadjie from
Togo opposed the motion by the prosecution. He stressed that there
was no provision in the Statute or Rules of the ICTR empowering
the international tribunal to hand over an accused person to a
national jurisdiction if the prosecutor seeks to withdraw charges
as in the present case.
</P>
<P>
"The prosecution should not act as a rubber stamp for some
national jurisdictions. It is a United Nations body," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, the defense counsel said, the tribunal should
request the Belgian government to hand over all the documents and
evidence against the accused to the tribunal to facilitate the
case.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. court will deliver a ruling on the motion on Thursday.
 At least 500,000 ethnic Tutsis and moderate Hutus were massacred
in a genocide that took place in the middle of 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Interior Minister Decides to Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Interior Minister Dinos
Michaelides said Wednesday he has decided to submit his
resignation to President Glafcos Clerides by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Michaelides' decision came only one day after the government
spokesman resigned for "a matter of principle" because he had
strongly disagreed with a cabinet decision, which exonerated
Michaelides from corruption allegations.
</P>
<P>
Michaelides had been accused by Christos Pourgourides,
president of the House of Representatives (parliament) Watchdog
Committee, for abuse of power at the immigration department and
unlawful enrichment through sale of apartments.
</P>
<P>
In a decision issued last Wednesday, the cabinet said that "no
further investigation is justified concerning the accusations."
</P>
<P>
Michaelides described his resignation as a political move to
protect Clerides, who a few months ago refused to accept
Michaelides' resignation following corruption accusation "from
increasing petty politics which have obvious objectives and
goals."
</P>
<P>
Thanking Clerides for his support and solidarity, the interior
minister said he intends to remain politically active.
</P>
<P>
Michaelides belongs to center-right Democratic Party (DIKO)
and served as interior minister in Clerides' first term in office
from 1993 to 1997, when DIKO was a coalition partner.
</P>
<P>
In late 1997 DIKO withdrew from the coalition, but Michaelides
decided to remain in the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
