<HEADLINE> New York to Hold a Hearing on Disputed Draw of Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The New York state Senate
Committee on Investigations said it would hold a hearing Thursday
on the disputed draw of last weekend's Evander Holyfield-Lennox
Lewis heavyweight title unification fight.
</P>
<P>
Among the witnesses scheduled to attend are fight judge Eugenia
Williams, who scored the fight in favor of Holyfield; referee
Arthur Mercante Jr,; and promoters Don King and Dino Duva.
</P>
<P>
Lewis might participate in person or by conference call. WBC
president Jose Sulaiman will speak by phone from Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
The state attorney general's office will hold a separate
hearing Friday, and the state athletic commission also is
investigating the fight.
</P>
<P>
The WBC judge, Larry O'Connell of England, said Tuesday that he
was surprised when he tallied his scorecard and found it was a
draw. But he said he made no mistake in judging the fight.
