<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Forms Task Force to Tackle Deadly Virus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Cabinet Wednesday
decided to set up a task force to tackle the outbreak of Japanese
encephalitis (JE), a deadly virus, in an integrated and
comprehensive manner.
</P>
<P>
The task force, to be headed by Health Minister Chua Jui Meng,
will comprise six ministries -- the Health Ministry, Agriculture
Ministry, Housing and Local Government Ministry, Information
Ministry, Defense Ministry and Home Ministry, according to the
Malaysian national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
The task force will hold its first meeting Thursday and make
recommendations to the Cabinet which wanted top priority to be
given by all the six ministries and agencies under them to tackle
the problem, Bernama quoted Chua as saying.
</P>
<P>
Chua said that the Cabinet had agreed in principle that some
kind of humanitarian assistance be given to the pig farmers
affected by the JE outbreak.
</P>
<P>
According to Chua, until Wednesday 87 people believed to have
been affected by the JE had been admitted to hospitals and there
had been 47 deaths so far, 15 in the northern state of Perak and
32 in the southern state of Negeri Sembilan.
</P>
<P>
The government has decided to destroy some 100,000 pigs from
these two areas and dispose the carcasses, Bernama quoted another
federal minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Transport Minister Ling Liong Sik said, "The Cabinet was very
unanimous that it (JE) is a very urgent issue... The main issue is
to save human lives, meaning that all those residing around pig
farms or high-risk areas needed to be vaccinated."
</P>
<P>
The deadly JE virus spreads from pigs to humans by the culex
mosquito. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
