<HEADLINE> Machinery, Electronics Remain China's Leading Foreign Trade Items </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Machinery and electronics
continued to be the leading items in China's foreign trade in 1998,
according to the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
China's imports and exports of machinery and electronics hit
130.4 billion U.S. dollars last year, up 9.9 percent from 1997.
This amount was 40.3 percent of China's total foreign trade volume
in 1998, up 3.6 percentage points from 1997, the ministry
announced at a meeting here today.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the exports and imports of machinery and
electronics totaled 65.54 billion US dollars and 63.87 billion US
dollars respectively in 1998, up 12.2 percent and 7.6 percent
respectively from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China's machinery and electronics exports to Asia
declined while those to Europe, the United States, and Africa
jumped an average of 20 percent, said Guan Liyan, deputy director
of the ministry's Machinery and Electronics Import and Export
Department.
</P>
<P>
Automatic digital processing equipment, video equipment, and
aviation materials were the major growth areas in China's
machinery and electronics exports last year, Guan said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that machinery and electronics exports by overseas-
funded enterprises stood at 40.1 billion U.S. dollars of machinery
and electronics last year, accounting for over 60 percent of the
national total.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> War Affects Tourism in Eritrea: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ASMARA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- War has affected Tourism in
Eritrea but the industry will recover before the year 2000
despite the on-going war with Ethiopia, Minister of Tourism Ahmed
Haj Ali said in Asmara Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The situation has bottomed out," Ahmed told Xinhua in an
interview here,

asserting that the war will not last forever.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest data provided by the ministry, the
inbound arrivals had dropped from 31,270 in May 1998 to 5,396 in
June of the year as a result of the outbreak of the Ethio-eritrean
border conflict.
</P>
<P>
"Tourism is a very sensitive sector," the minister said, noting
that even when there is natural catastrophe or epidemic, it is the
first sector to be affected.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed said that tourism has been affected after Ethiopia
imposed air and sea embargo on Eritrea. The three times a week
flights between Asmara and Addis ababa, capital of Ethiopia, was
forced to stop due to the escalating war.
</P>
<P>
Previously, tourism showed rosy signs in Eritrea as the
international tourist arrivals recorded 315,417 in 1995, followed
by 416,595 and 409,544 in 1996 and 1997 respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, because of the lasting war between the two horn of
Africa neighbors, the inbound arrivals in Eritrea went down to
187,720 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Since the conflict will not last forever, he said, the
international tourists are still coming, though not as many as
expected.
</P>
<P>
After all, he noted, the more than 1,000 kilometers of coast
line along the Red Sea, some 360 islands, excellent diving sites
with clean and unpolluted water, as well as the cultural
diversity, are all attractions for overseas tourists.
</P>
<P>
As the minister put it, one of the great civilizations was in
Eritrea and its capital Asmara has been dubbed as "the world of
arts dec o."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, Eritrea is full of potential with all kinds
of tourism including eco-tourism and cultural tourism.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea targets Europe as its major market, Ahmed said, citing
Italy, Germany, Britain, France and the Nordic countries.
</P>
<P>
In America, he said, Eritrea plans to attract tourists from the
United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
He said that in Middle East, Eritrea is looking at tourists
from Saudi Arabia and other countries in the Gulf Region.
</P>
<P>
In Asia, he said Eritrea sets eyes on Japan and the Republic of
Korea, while in Africa, it expect tourists from Sudan, Rwanda and
Uganda. Of course, he noted that before the conflict Ethiopia was
a major source of the inbound tourists.
</P>
<P>
Divestment in tourism as one major part of Eritrea's
privatization program has contributed much to the development of
the sector.
</P>
<P>
In fact, most of the state-run hotels had been privatized, the
minister said, noting that most of the big state-run hotels such
as Keren and Dahlak had been sold out.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said the state-run Ambasoira Hamasein Hotel,
named after a mountain in the province of Hamasein, formerly
called the Imperial Hotel, will be privatized this month or next
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
