<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Senior Finance Officials Meet in Hanoi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Senior finance officials from ASEAN
countries met here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting were deputy finance ministers and deputy
central bank governors from the nine ASEAN countries as well as
the deputy secretary-general of the ASEAN Secretariat and their
delegations.
</P>
<P>
This is part of a series of meetings to prepare for the Third
ASEAN Finance Ministers Meeting (AFMM) slated for March 19 and 20
in Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
the meeting discussed its report to the ministers, which
focused on two topics: the progress made in ASEAN financial
cooperation in order to follow up the Hanoi Action Plan and the
decisions of the Sixth ASEAN Summit held last December in Hanoi;
and proposed approaches and schedule for the working program in
the time to come, in particular the urgent prioritized measures to
help expediting the recovery process and growth in the region.
</P>
<P>
The proposed issues being submitted to the ministers for
consideration are attraction of capital flows, international
financial architecture, strengthening international consultation
and dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The "9+3" meeting of vice-finance ministers and vice-governors
of central banks will be held here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Minister of Finance Jin Liqun and Vice Governor of
the People's Bank of China Xiao Gang will join their counterparts
from Japan and the Republic of Korea and the nine members of the
ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
