<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Faces Electricity Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is suffering a shortage of
electricity during the current dry season, Vietnam News Agency
(VNA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam will face an estimated shortage of about 600 million
kwh of electricity this dry season because of the shortage of
investment capital for power projects, slow construction and the
imbalance between electricity consumption at peak and off-peak
hours, VNA quoted Director General of Electricity of Vietnam (EVN)
Hoang Trung Hai as saying.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, Hai said, electricity output has increased by 2.3
billion kwh and additional charge capacity has increased by 350 mw
annually.
</P>
<P>
However, to ensure the supply during the dry season, Vietnam's
power industry has to increase its output annually by between 400
and 500 mw and needs an investment capital of 13-16 trillion
Vietnamese dong (935 to 1,151 million U.S. dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
Although the power industry has mobilized capital for building
more power plants, it has not met the above-mentioned demand. The
industry has supplied an additional combined output of only 550 mw
in the 1995-1998 period.
</P>
<P>
To ease the shortage, EVN has taken drastic steps, focusing on
the maintenance and repair of power plant equipment. It has run
all its thermal power plants, diesel and gas turbines since late
1998 to meet the demand, Hai said.
</P>
<P>
EVN will coordinate with the mass media to call for minimal
electricity consumption in addition to seeking other electricity
sources and preparing options to alleviate the power shortage in
the dry season, Hai added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
