<HEADLINE> Horticulture Turns Major Cash Earner for Kenya: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mudavadi made the remarks while opening of the sixth
Horticulture Trade Exhibition, known as Hortec '99, the largest
and most influential show of its kind in Africa, at the Kenyatta
International Conference Center in the Kenyan capital of Nairobi
here.
</P>
<P>
During the show, over 110 exhibitors from South Africa, the
Netherlands, France, Israel, Spain, Britain and Kenya are
displaying over 200 species of flowers.
</P>
<P>
Seeds, greenhouse facilities, pesticides and fungicides, as
well as machinery, equipment and tools related to horticultural
production are also on display.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that horticulture is an important rural
occupation, and last year the sector earned the country a record
50 billion Kenya shillings (about 820 million U.S. dollars) in
output value.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in 1998 the horticultural sector in the county
exported nearly 79,000 tons of produce, raking in 14 billion
shillings and accounting for some 13 percent of Kenya's foreign
exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
Kenya had increased its market share at the Dutch auctions from
17 percent in 1993 to over 28 percent only three years later, and
is a leading exporter of cut flowers and related produce to
Europe, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that although horticulture now is the fourth highest
foreign exchange earner after tea, coffee and tourism, it has the
potential to emerge as Kenya's most important industry.
</P>
<P>
Occupying about 11 percent of the country's arable land,
horticulture becomes the source of income for many Kenyans, he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Event and Conference Organizer Ltd., the
sponsor of the

Hortec '99, five seminar sessions on horticulture will be held
during the event, focusing on horticulture in east and central
Africa, financial management and technical issues, laboratory
services, trade and marketing.
</P>
<P>
During the 10-day show, lectures will also be presented by
experts from Holland, Britain and France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
