<HEADLINE> Israel's Right-Wing Party Leader Convicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Aryeh Deri, leader of Israel's
powerful right-wing Shas Party, Wednesday was convicted of
bribe-taking by Jerusalem District Court.
</P>
<P>
Judge Yaakov Tzemach announced the verdicts on Wednesday
morning before reading a 917-page decision.
</P>
<P>
The judge said that Deri took about 160,000 U.S. dollars in
bribes in return for using his senior position in the Interior
Ministry to provide some organizations with special treatment and
government funding.
</P>
<P>
Deri, a close associate of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu,
was also convicted of fraud and breaching public trust. The judge
also sharply criticized that Deri had obstructed justice during
the investigation by exploiting his right of keeping silence.
</P>
<P>
Although Deri was acquitted on some other charges against him,
the bribery conviction carries a maximum sentence of seven years
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
The sentencing is due to take place on Thursday of next week.
</P>
<P>
According to Israel's law, Deri will be legally barred from
serving as a cabinet minister for 10 years from the day he
finishes serving his sentence.
</P>
<P>
In response, Deri's lawyer said that Deri totally rejected the
verdict and will appeal to the supreme court. Deri himself told
reporters that he will make an "orderly reaction" after a careful
consideration.
</P>
<P>
Shas Party, which currently has 10 seats in the 120-member
Knesset (parliament), is made up of Jews with Middle Eastern
origin.
</P>
<P>
Since it is only less than two months before the general
elections of Israel, Deri's conviction is likely to raise
tensions in the country.
</P>
<P>
Followers of Shas regarded the conviction as a ruling against
the whole party. And several hundred demonstrators protested
outside the court and near Deri's home. One demonstrator was
detained by police.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that "this is a difficult day," but called on
the supporters of Shas to respect the law and act with restraint.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, local political analysts said that the
verdict could rally Shas supporters to the polls and help the
right-wing Netanyahu in the elections.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli police have been bracing for the verdict's
announcement, with assigning a bodyguard to each of the three
Jerusalem District Court judges who presided over the case and
reinforcing security around the court.
</P>
<P>
Police said said the judges received death threats several
times over the last few days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
