<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK House of Lords to Rule on Pinochet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 17 (Xinhua)-- The United Kingdom's Highest Court,
the House of Lords, will rule in one week on whether former
Chilean leader Augusto Pinochet is immune from arrest and
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
"The rule will be issued next Wednesday at 2 p.m.," a spokesman
for the House of Lords told Xinhua on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet, 83, is still under house arrest in a mansion outside
London, waiting for a ruling on his claim to immunity.
</P>
<P>
He was arrested on October 16 at a London hospital at the
request of a Spanish judge.
</P>
<P>
Spain wants to extradite Pinochet and put him on trial for
accused crimes including genocide and torture committed under his
17-year rule in Chile, which ended in 1990. The Spanish judge said
Pinochet was responsible for the deaths and disappearances of 3,
000 people.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet's lawyers argued that he should enjoy immunity from
prosecution as a former head of state.
</P>
<P>
Last November, the House of Lords ruled that Pinochet had no
immunity from prosecution. But it had to set aside the ruling
after Pinochet's lawyers accused that one of the five Lords in the
panel had links with Amnesty International, the human rights body
which strongly supports Pinochet's prosecution.
</P>
<P>
The new panel formed by seven Lords held a three-week-long
rehearing of the case early this year without reaching an
immediate rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
