<HEADLINE> Sino-Italian Economic Ties Expected To Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Investment and trade between
China and Italy are expected to grow because of President Jiang
Zemin's visit to Italy at the end of this month, analysts here say.
</P>
<P>
China considers Italy an important trade partner in the EU. The
two countries had an overall trade increase last year of 3.5
percent to 4.8 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Chinese exports to Italy grew 15.1 percent to 2.577 billion
dollars, but imports declined 7.1 percent to 2.277 billion dollars,
according to China's General Customs Administration.
</P>
<P>
China mainly exports machinery and electronics products,
garments, and textile products and imports mainly textile
machinery, rubber and plastic processing machinery, and leather
products.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, Italy had launched 1,254 projects in China,
involving 2.1 billion U.S. dollars in Italian investment. Italy is
second only to Germany in Europe in technology transfers to China.
From 1981 to 1998, China imported 1,262 items of technology from
Italy, worth 7.2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The two countries' economies complement each other, analysts
say, and bilateral investment and trade still have great potential.
</P>
<P>
Small and medium-sized companies play a leading role in Italy's
business. China's Foreign Trade Minister Shi Guangsheng says that
Italian companies are welcome to invest in and transfer technology
to China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
