<HEADLINE> Most Urban Chinese Travel at Least Once Yearly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- About 60 percent of China's big-
city residents now travel domestically at least once a year,
according to a recent survey conducted by the China Youth Daily in
China's three major cities of Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that 61.9 percent of Shanghai residents
are likely to join travel groups, while 82 percent of Beijingers
say they would rather travel by themselves or with their relatives
and friends.
</P>
<P>
During this year's Spring Festival vacation in February, the
survey pointed out, more than 18 million Chinese traveled, and
spent about 14 billion yuan (1.7 billion U.S. dollars) doing so.
</P>
<P>
Also during the Spring Festival holiday, according to the
survey, some 100,000 Beijingers, and even more Guangzhou residents,
traveled to Southeast Asian countries and regions. In Shanghai,
the number of people traveling abroad was twice those of last year.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that this increased travel will contribute
significantly to the expansion of domestic demand in China and
create more job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
At a conference on economic work held by the Central Committee
of the Communist Party of China last year, the tourism sector was
listed as one of the country's economic-growth focal points.
</P>
</TEXT>
