<HEADLINE> British Press Names Solana, Prodi, Guterres For EU Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The names appearing frequently on leading newspapers are: NATO
Secretary General Javier Solana, former Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi and Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio Guterres.
</P>
<P>
"Speculation on a successor to Mr Santer centered on Javier
Solana, Secretary General of NATO, and Romano Prodi, former
Italian Prime Minister," the Financial Times said.
</P>
<P>
The Times reported that the "most mentioned candidates" are
Solana and Prodi.
</P>
<P>
It also said British Prime Minister Tony Blair was against
naming a stop-gap president.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Telegraph said two leading "heavyweights" favoured by
Britain were Guterres and Prodi.
</P>
<P>
But none of the newspapers have disclosed their sources for
their reports.
</P>
<P>
Jacques Santer and the entire commission resigned on Tuesday in
the wake of a damming report which accused the executive body of
corruption and mismanagement. They are now remaining for the
present in a caretaker capacity.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair told the Parliament on
Tuesday that Santer should step down "soon as possible". He said
the mass resignation of the commission members offered a chance to
do "root and branch reform in Europe". 
