<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lao People's Revolutionary Party Holds Eighth Plenum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Lao People's Revolutionary
Party (LPRP) Central Committee has concluded its eighth plenum (VI
Congress) in Vientiane, urging the whole party, the army and the
people to exert every effort to implement the socio-economic
development plan, Lao official news agency KPL reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The plenum was held from March 9 to 16 under the chairmanship
of its President Khamtay Siphandone.
</P>
<P>
Despite the impact of the regional economic-monetary crisis,
the plenum agreed that, in enhancing the spirit of independence
and striving for further self-reliance, the party-state has
decided to concentrate its investment on agricultural production
and irrigation expansion.
</P>
<P>
The rice-growing area has been increased to 87,000 hectares in
the 1998-1999 dry season, a rise of 34,000 hectares over the
1997-1998 period. Farmers' incomes are on the rise. Development in
the industrial, communications and transport sectors is
continuing.
</P>
<P>
Attention has been paid to rural development, market management
and financial-monetary management. Accordingly, the growth of
the country's socio-economic basis is being continually ensured.
</P>
<P>
The plenary meeting examined in some depth defects,
shortcomings and other negative phenomena which may have arisen in
the process of implementation of the party-state line and
policies.
</P>
<P>
However, the plenum noted that Laos still faces
economic-financial difficulties. The impacts are felt strongly on
the whole system of national economy. The living conditions of
civil servants and low-income earners are in the doldrums, said
the plenum.
</P>
<P>
Under the circumstances, the plenum called for ensuring
political stability and social order, restoring the national
economy to normal as soon as possible, easing the low living
conditions of civil servants and people, and maintaining the
continual pace of the country's socio-economic development.
</P>
<P>
The participants discussed and made preliminary comments on
the drafting of strategies for a national socio-economic
development plan for the period up to year 2020. 
</P>
</TEXT>
