<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment to Pakistan Drops to 222M Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct investment (FDI)
to Pakistan dropped by 41.2 percent to 222.2 million U.S. dollars
in the first seven months of the current fiscal year starting from
July 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the State Bank of Pakistan, the total
private investment inflow during the seven months amounted to
235.5 million dollars, which included portfolio investment of 13.3
million dollars, showing a dramatically decline of 56.5 percent
compared with the same months of last year.
</P>
<P>
During the corresponding period of last year, the total inflow
of private investment stood at 542.3 million dollars including
377.8 million dollars of FDI and 164.5 million dollars of
portfolio investment.
</P>
<P>
The United States and the United Kingdom remained the major
contributors of the FDI inflow in the first seven months of the
current year with 94.9 million dollars and 50 million dollars
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The other noted countries are Japan (21.1 million dollars),
Germany (17.5 million dollars), France (6.5 million dollars),
South Korea (4.6 million dollars) and the Netherlands (4.5 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, when compared with the corresponding period of last
year, except for Japan, Germany, South Korea and France, the
investment showed a considerable decline.
</P>
<P>
The major decline was witnessed in the inflows from the United
States as the FDI in the first seven months declined to 94.9
million dollars as against 169 million dollars in the same period
of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
