<HEADLINE> Japan's Fiscal 1999 Budget Passed Despite Opposition in Upper House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government's annual
budget for fiscal 1999 was enacted intact Wednesday despite a
rejection by the opposition-controlled House of Councilors.
</P>
<P>
The budget bill was voted down by opposition parties in the
upper chamber earlier in the day, but it still became law as Japan'
s Constitution gives the House of Representatives supremacy over
the upper chamber in adopting a government budget.
</P>
<P>
The budget cleared the lower house on February 19, backed by
the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and its coalition
partner Liberal Party (LP), which enjoy a majority in the lower
chamber.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's passage through the Diet (parliament) marks the
earliest date for a national budget to be enacted in Japan since
the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
The fiscal 1999 budget features expenditures worth 81.86
trillion yen (about 690.5 billion dollars), designed by the
Japanese government to help revitalize the slumping domestic
economy.
</P>
<P>
It is up 5.4 percent over the initial budget of the current
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
To fund this expansionary budget, the Japanese government has
to float a record 71.13 trillion yen (about 599.5 billion dollars)
worth of bonds, including refinancing bonds needed to redeem
outstanding bonds coming due during the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
