<HEADLINE> FAO Picks Philippines as Pilot Fishery Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The United Nation's Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) has chosen the Philippines as one
of the three countries to pilot-test a three-year fishery project
which is expected to further develop the country's marine
resources and help liberate small fishermen from poverty.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released by Agriculture Department
Secretary William Dar, the project, dubbed as the Forum for
Sustainable Fisheries (FSF), is geared at assisting developing
countries to better manage their fisheries and other oceanic
resources.
</P>
<P>
The project also aims to alleviate poverty, help local fishing
communities become self-sufficient, and secure the bounty and the
rich biodiversity of the sea for future generations.
</P>
<P>
The FSF, which will be implemented from next year to 2002, has
a three-year budget of 7.25 million U.S. dollars to be sourced
from foundations, other donors and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Of the total budget, some 640,000 dollars is set for pilot
operations in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The other countries eyed by the FAO as pilot FSF countries are
Guyana and Madagascar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
