<HEADLINE> Thailand Wants to Become World Major Food Supplier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is taking steps to
become a major food producer for the world by year 2020, a senior
Thai government official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Science, Technology and Environment would
double its efforts on scientific research, technological
development, energy exploitation and environmental protection to
achieve this goal, said Santhad Somchevita, permanent secretary
for the ministry.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference in commemoration of the ministry's
20th anniversary that the ministry realizes the significance of
turning to the development of scientific technology through
concrete research and development projects to increase the quality
of life of the Thai people, and enhance the country's economic
potential and competitiveness, especially in the food trade.
</P>
<P>
Projects for the development and improvement of food production
with a parallel significance given to the development of energy
and environmental protection were believed to be a practical
mechanism that would enable Thailand to achieve its goal of
becoming a major supplier of food to the world over the next 20
years, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the policy coincided with a move by authorities in
various agencies to promote Thailand as an exporter of
chemical-free farm products in the future by developing the
organic farming through transgenic techniques.
</P>
<P>
The techniques, aimed at reducing the use of chemical
substances in growing cash crops and plants, involve transferring
genetic material from one organism to another to create a new
strain with the desired characteristics, he said.
</P>
<P>
Scientists said transgenic techniques would lead to the faster
development of new strains at lower costs. They suggested that the
resulted products would be more uniform in quality that farmers
could be sure of successful crops and maximum output. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
