<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exports of automobiles
and parts are expected to increase remarkably this year as local
creditors rebuild confidence and begin to extend new loans to the
industry, the Thai News Agency (TNA) Wednesday quoted a top
businessman as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ninnanart Chaithiraphinyo, chairman of the Automobile Industry
Group of the Federation of Thai Industries, said that exports of
cars, motorcycles and parts were believed to reach 150,000 units,
worth 100 billion baht (2.7 billion U.S. dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
The figure will more than double last year's volume of 66,788
units worth 44 billion baht (1.2 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The change coincided with a positive move by local creditors
which began offering new loans to automobile and parts firms due
to improved export prospects of the industry, Ninnanart said.
</P>
<P>
Creditors are regaining their confidence that lendings to the
industry would not turn to be non-performing loan, he added.
</P>
<P>
Domestic automobile sale was also expected to rise to
160,000-180,000 units this year, an increase of 10 to 20 percent
over last year, he predicted. 
