<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Reduces School Enrolment in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African Unity
(OAU) says the spread of HIV/AIDS has lowered the return of
investment in the educational sector in Africa.
</P>
<P>
An OAU document entitled "HIV/AIDS and Education: One Affecting
the Other" prepared for the conference of African ministers of
education taking pace in Harare, capital of Zimbabwe, said African
governments should, therefore, work toward minimizing the spread
of the infection.
</P>
<P>
"In many places children born with HIV/AIDS have not lived to
enroll in schools or those who enrolled dropped out due to health
problems or taking care of sick relatives," said the document,
which is available here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It said the infection had brought economic hardships to many
African families making them unable to send children to school.
</P>
<P>
"The spread of HIV/AIDS has brought economic difficulties to
families, and this has negative impact on the demand for
education," it said.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. AIDS report for 1996 estimated that the number of people
infected with HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, had increased from
10 million in 1990 to about 25.5 million.
</P>
<P>
In Africa it was estimated that by the year 2000 about 20
million people would be HIV positive, causing approximately one
million deaths annually.
</P>
<P>
The document recommended that schools alter the content and
methods of teaching to include knowledge about sexuality, the
transmission and prevention of the infection and skills to cope
with its impact on schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
