<P>
MANILA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada has formed a seven-member task force to monitor and
regulate the importation of petrochemical and plastics products as
a way to protect the country's fledging petrochemical and plastics
industries from unfair trade practices like dumping and outright
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
An administrative order said the task force was empowered to
withhold the issuance of Importation Clearance (IC) if there is
basis to believe that the shipment has been tainted with any
unfair trade practice.
</P>
<P>
The president also vested the task force with the power to seek
the assistance of the Department of Justice and the Philippine
National Police in the apprehension and prosecution of elements
involved in the smuggling of petrochemical and plastics products.
</P>
<P>
"The government is determined to ensure the survival and
continued growth of the country's newly-established petrochemical
and plastics industries and to see to it that the same is placed
in a level playing field vis-a-vis its foreign counterparts,"
Estrada said in the administrative order.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is aware that during times of economic
crisis, there exist rampant unfair trade practices involving
dumping, underevaluation, misclassification and outright smuggling
of petrochemical and plastics products.
</P>
<P>
Estrada also cited the need to protect the government's
flagship projects like the petrochemical and plastics industry in
view of its critical role in pump priming the national economy,
generating jobs, and reducing the country's reliance on foreign
exchange.
</P>
<P>
The head of the task force shall have a term of one year.
</P>
</TEXT>
