<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Set Up Bank to Support Informal Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa has directed the establishment of the Dar es
Salaam Community Bank to provide micro-finance credit facilities
to the informal sector.
</P>
<P>
Launching the Dar es Salaam Informal Sector Development Program
(1999- 2003) Tuesday, Mkapa said that the informal sector
development can reduce unemployment, eradicate poverty and cut
down the crime rate.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers Wednesday quoted the Dar es Salaam City
Commission (DCC) Chairman Charles Keenja as saying that his
commission will this year provide more than 900 million shillings
(one U.S. dollar equals 692 Tanzanian shillings at present) worth
soft loans to the sector.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa gave the directive when he was on a one-day inspection
tour of the informal sector in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
"The government is now giving a special emphasis on individuals
and groups who employ themselves or form co-operative unions and
initiate credit and savings schemes," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president disclosed that the launching of the informal
sector development program was the government's long-term plan in
transition to transform the informal sector into the formal
sector.
</P>
<P>
He directed authorities concerned to reduce unnecessary
bureaucracy which block the access to loan applicants.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mkapa also warned the informal sector that they
should cultivate a habit of repaying loans and keep away from
hiring child labors. The DCC recovered only 14 percent of the
total loans disbursed to Dar es Salaam residents in the 1997/98
financial year, he concluded  
</P>
</TEXT>
