<HEADLINE> Burundi Peace Committees Proceed Slowly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Four committees for the
Burundi peace talks ended their 10-day meeting Tuesday in
Tanzanian northern town of Arusha with some but slow progress.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers Wednesday quoted sources close to the talks as
saying another round of meeting is needed in May before the
decisive plenary session in June.
</P>
<P>
Concluding the meeting, the international peace facilitator,
Tanzanian founding president Julius Nyerere, urged the committees
to iron out their differences toward a lasting peace for the
war-torn central African nation.
</P>
<P>
Delegates to the closed-door talks said that the committees
have started more in-depth discussions between warring parties,
but progress is slow especially on the issues of peace and
democracy.
</P>
<P>
Nicholas Haysom, the South African president of the democracy
committee, said that his committee has completed preliminary
discussions on a 36- issue agenda, but some most difficult issues
remained unsolved.
</P>
<P>
He said the problems were related to an electoral system, the
composition of the legislature, local government and institutions.
</P>
<P>
Haysom said it was likely that another set of committee
negotiations will be organized in Arusha ahead of the June
deadline, but he believed Burundi nationals are expecting to
"sort out the problem by the end of the year".
</P>
<P>
On January 23, the Great Lakes Region countries suspended the
economic sanctions, imposed on Burundi since July 1996 when
former Burundi president Pierre Buyoya took power following a
military coup. They aimed to encourage the progress achieved in
the four round talks which started last June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
