<HEADLINE> Australian dollar Closes Slightly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed a
little higher Wednesday after being trounced in recent days by the
falling gold price.
</P>
<P>
At the close of trading the Australian dollar was buying 62.57
U.S. cents from 62.64 U.S. cents Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The currency this week has cast off almost one U.S. cent from
its 63.47 U.S. cents close Monday, as the gold price lost about
8.00 U.S. dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
The gold price was Wednesday around 283.75 U.S. dollars an
ounce, from 291.50 U.S. dollars Monday.
</P>
<P>
Comments from French president Jacques Chirac that the
International Monetary Fund should sell its gold stocks to aid
debtor nations started the ball rolling for gold prices on Monday
and U.S. President Bill Clinton added his weight, supporting those
comments Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
At the close of trading Wednesday the Australian dollar was
buying 0.5691 euro from 0.5788 euro Tuesday, while the euro was
trading at 1.0995 U.S. dollars from 1.0824 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was buying 74.23 Japanese yen from 73.62
yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
