<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Faces Maize Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is faced with a
massive shortage of maize, one of the staple food in the country,
this year as scorching heat and low rainfall ruined huge areas of
crops, The Star paper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Maize output is now expected to reach 5.81 million tons instead
of the 7. 26 million forecast two weeks ago, the National Maize
Producers' Organization (NAMPO) said.
</P>
<P>
Low yields were also expected in other crops due to unusual
weather since mid-February.
</P>
<P>
Some farmers in the maize-growing areas had indicated that
their crops were up to 30 percent below expectations, NAMPO
president Japie Grobler said.
</P>
<P>
Once the season was over there would be an estimated shortage
of one million tons, he said.
</P>
<P>
As a low harvest was also expected for other regional
countries, South Africa would have to fulfil its commitments of
feeding them, which would aggravate the situation.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has asked for 400,000 tons, Zambia between 300,000 and
500,000 tons and Namibia about 60,000 tons, Grobler said.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa would buy maize from other countries. The
first shipment of Argentine maize would be landed within the next
few weeks, he said.
</P>
<P>
Climatic conditions have hit the agricultural sector hard over
the past few years, cutting its foreign exchange earnings from
eight billion rand (1. 3 billion U.S. dollars) to four billion
rand (67 million dollars) last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
