<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Establish Three Border Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is to establish three
border markets with Niger, Cameroun and Chad to boost exports and
enhance business relations with its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The three proposed markets are to be set up this year by the
Borno State, northeastern Nigeria, bordering these countries,
according to a Business Guardian report Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Borno State Administrator Group Captain Lawan Ningi Haruna was
quoted as saying at the recently concluded Kaduna trade fair that
the establishment of border markets is a strategy to boost
socio-economic activities along the border towns.
</P>
<P>
He noted that manufacturers and industrialists of the four
countries will use the markets as a common ground to exchange
their goods and services.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, he added, the rate of smuggling along the border
will also be reduced when the products and services are available
at market prices.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the major objectives of the government to set up
border markets, the administrator stated.
</P>
<P>
The idea of establishing border markets to formalize Nigeria's
exports with its neighbors was advocated by the then President of
the Association of Nigerian Exporters, late Chief Grace Ogunlusi,
in late 1980s.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
