<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Call for Arab Support over Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians Wednesday called
on the Arab countries to provide political and financial support
for the issue of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Egypt's Voice of Arab radio, Palestinian
Minister for Jerusalem Affairs Faisal Husseini urged Arab foreign
ministers to seek ways of protecting Jerusalem against Israel's
move of judaization.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministers Council of the Arab League opened the
111th session here in the day. The ministers are expected to
discuss, among other things, the issue of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Husseini lauded the stance of the European Union (EU) on
Jerusalem, stressing the need for the EU and its member states to
play a key role in the Middle East peace process, the Cairo-based
radio said.
</P>
<P>
The EU maintains that Jerusalem is part of the occupied
territories, disagreeing to Israel's proclamation that the holy
city is its "undivided and eternal capital."
</P>
<P>
Israel occupied the traditionally Arab East Jerusalem in the
1967 Mideast War and its parliament later passed a bill, claiming
that the city, holy to Muslims, Christians and Jews, is Israel's
capital.
</P>
<P>
Husseini lashed out at Israel's threats over the possible
declaration of a Palestinian state, noting that peace is in the
interests of both the Palestinians and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have said they will declare an independent
state on May 4 when the five-year Palestinian interim self-rule
enshrined in the 1993 Oslo Accord expires regardless of the
results of the peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel has threatened to take tough measures against the step,
including annexation of parts of the West Bank under its control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Right-Wing Party Leader Convicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Aryeh Deri, leader of Israel's
powerful right-wing Shas Party, Wednesday was convicted of
bribe-taking by Jerusalem District Court.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution charged that Deri took about 167,000 U.S.
dollars in bribes in return for using his senior position in the
Interior Ministry to provide some organizations with special
treatment and government funding.
</P>
<P>
Judge Yaakov Tzemach announced the verdicts on Wednesday
morning before reading a 917-page decision.
</P>
<P>
Deri, a close associate of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu,
was also convicted of fraud and breaching the public trust.
</P>
<P>
Although Deri was acquitted on some other charges against him,
the bribery conviction would carry a maximum sentence of seven
years imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
It is still not clear when the sentencing will take place.
</P>
<P>
According to Israel's law, Deri will be legally barred from
serving as a cabinet minister for 10 years from the day he
finishes serving his sentence.
</P>
<P>
Shas Party, which currently has 10 seats in the 120-member
Knesset (parliament), is made up of Jews with Middle Eastern
origin.
</P>
<P>
Since it is only less than two months before the general
elections of Israel, Deri's conviction is likely to raise
tensions in the country.
</P>
<P>
Some followers of Shas regarded the conviction as a ruling
against the whole party and threatened to hold mass
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
However, local political analysts said that the verdict could
rally Shas supporters to the polls and help the right-wing
Netanyahu in the elections.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli police has been bracing for the verdict's
announcement, by assigning a bodyguard to each of the three
Jerusalem District Court judges who presided over the case, and
reinforcing security around the court.
</P>
<P>
Police said the judges received death threats several times
over the last few days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
