<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Suffers Big Defeat: Eritrean Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ASMARA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian army had suffered
the biggest defeat in the Tsorona front since the outbreak of the
conflict between the two Horn of Africa neighbors, the Eritrean
Foreign Ministry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a statement that Eritrea destroyed a total
of 57 Ethiopian tanks, captured six others and shot down one
Mig-23 jet fighter in the three-day fierce fighting at the Tsorona
flank of the Alitiena-Mereb front.
</P>
<P>
The fighting died down at about 9:00 a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia denied the downing of the Mig-fighter, although one
senior Eritrean foreign ministry official said that the plane
crashed in the Ethiopian side.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean statement said that Ethiopia had lost about 9,000
troops in the battles which raged from February 23 to 26 in the
Mereb-Setit front.
</P>
<P>
It noted that "their losses in the Tsorona front in the past
three days were several fold higher."
</P>
<P>
The statement pointed out that the Ethiopian forces bombed the
small town of Kinafina in central-south Eritrea Tuesday, severely
wounding eight people.
</P>
<P>
It added that in the previous weeks, Ethiopia bombed the
civilian centers of Deda Lailai, Shambuqo, Adi Quala and a cluster
of villages in the Zalambesa area.
</P>
<P>
No fighting was reported Tuesday and Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
