<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA Warns Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- FIFA, the world soccer governing
body, has warned the Zambian government not to take any action
that might be in variance with the FIFA Statutes as it seek to
resolve the standoff with the Football Association of Zambia (FAZ)
executive, the Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted FIFA as saying that it has given the
government and the FAZ enough time to find an amicable solution to
the 11-month standoff but no meaningful progress has been made.
</P>
<P>
FIFA accused the government of gross interference in the
running of the sport and said that Zambia's soccer will collapse
if FAZ does not receive any grants from the government, according
to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Following Zambia's poor performance at the Africa Cup finals in
Burkina Faso in February of 1998, the FAZ executive was removed on
the charge of misapplication of more than 500 million Kwacha (over
200,000 U.S. dollars) the government released for the campaign.
</P>
<P>
FIFA, reacting to what it saw as government interference in the
running of soccer, was on the verge of banning Zambia from
international soccer activities when the government reluctantly
restored in office the FAZ executive led by Teddy Mulonga.
</P>
<P>
Later the government allowed Mulonga and his team back in
office but it imposed a financial squeeze on the association in a
bid to force the current executives out.
</P>
<P>
The estrangement of the FAZ executive has cast a shadow on the
future of Zambian soccer given the fact the association is
dependent on the government financial support to fulfill its
various international engagements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
