<HEADLINE> Share Prices Down Sharply on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 17 (Xinhua)-- Share prices Fell sharply on
Singapore Stock Market Wednesday depressed by profit-taking on
large capitalized shares.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index was down 19.38 points to end
at 1,470.16 amid selling by institutions in modest volume.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the total turnover increased to 156.51 million units
valued at 234.36 million Singapore dollars (135.82 million U.S.
dollars). Falling stocks led gainers by 159 to 62 with 206
counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
UIC w99 topped the actives list with a volume of 23.32 million
shares. UIC was the second most heavily traded stock with 20.18
million units done. DBS Land was the next with 10.59 million
shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Thai Pr led the gainers of the day with a gain of 14 cents to
close at 4.10 U.S. dollars. It was followed by Asean and Sp Ld
that edged up 10 cents to finish at 6.40 U.S. dollars and 3.74
Singapore dollars respectively. Jar Mat was the next with a
pick-up of eight cents to end at 3.26 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 and SPH led the losers of the day
dropping 60 cents to finish at 21.40 and 19.70 Singapore dollars
respectively. SPH 100 and UOB F shed off 50 cents and ended at
19.70 and 10.40 Singapore dollars respectively. SIF sank 30 cents
to close at 12.70 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers noted that overnight loss on Wall Street led to a weak
opening and the pressure on the DBS Land stock also dampened the
market sentiment.
</P>
<P>
DBS Land, the major property developer in the city state,
announced after Tuesday's session that it suffered a loss of 239
million Singapore dollars (139 million U.S. dollars) for 1998.
This was the first loss by the DBS Land since its listing 12 years
ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
