<HEADLINE> Machinery, Electronics Remain China's Leading Foreign Trade Items </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Machinery and electronics
continued to be the leading items in China's foreign trade in 1998,
according to the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
China's imports and exports of machinery and electronics hit
130.4 billion U.S. dollars last year, up 9.9 percent from 1997.
This amount was 40.3 percent of China's total foreign trade volume
in 1998, up 3.6 percentage points from 1997, the ministry
announced at a meeting here today.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, the machinery grew 12.2 percent to 65.54 billion
U.S. dollars and electronics increased 7.6 percent to 63.87
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China's machinery and electronics exports to Asia
declined while those to Europe, the United States, and Africa
jumped an average of 20 percent, said Guan Liyan, deputy director
of the ministry's Machinery and Electronics Import and Export
Department.
</P>
<P>
Automatic digital processing equipment, video equipment, and
aviation materials were the major growth areas in China's
machinery and electronics exports last year, Guan said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that machinery and electronics exports by overseas-
funded enterprises stood at 40.1 billion U.S. dollars of machinery
and electronics last year, accounting for over 60 percent of the
national total.  
</P>
</TEXT>
