<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Opposes Total Ban on Use of Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is not considering
signing the Ottawa Convention which slaps a total ban on the use
of mines because doing so would be against its vital security
requirements, Pakistani Foreign Office sources said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan's peculiar security requirements do not permit
accepting a ban on the use of land mines as stipulated under the
Ottawa Convention," the Associated Press of Pakistan quoted the
sources as saying here.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan cannot sign the Ottawa Convention which totally bans
the use of land mines "unless and until a viable alternative to
land mines is available," said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Russia and India have also refused to sign
the convention for their own respective security reasons, the
sources noted.
</P>
<P>
However, the sources said Pakistan has all along been observing
high standards of regulating the use of mines keeping in view the
humanitarian concern on the use of land mines.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has already banned the export of anti-personnel land
mines in pursuance of its unilateral moratorium since March 1997
on export of land mines.
</P>
<P>
It accepts the provisions of the amended Protocol II of the
Certain Conventional Weapons Convention which it ratified on March
9 this year.
</P>
<P>
Drawing the distinction between the Ottawa Convention and the
amended Protocol II, the sources said the latter doesn't impose a
ban on the use of land mines but regulates their use.
</P>
<P>
The amended Protocol II calls for elimination by 2007 of all
"dumb" land mines which are without detectable, self-destruction
and self-deactivation mechanism.
</P>
<P>
The formal acceptance by Pakistan of the amended Protocol II
reflects its firm commitment towards the humanitarian cause of
sparing innocent civilians of the scourge of anti-personnel mines,
said the sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
