<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Down on Wall Street, Gold Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Following four consecutive
record breaking days, the Australian sharemarket fell Wednesday,
depressed by a dip on Wall Street and lower gold prices.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index slipped 14.4 points or
almost half a percent to close at 2,977.8, up off its 2,968.0
intra-day low.
</P>
<P>
Macquarie Nevitts Director Brad Usasz said the Tuesday night
dip on Wall Street threw the local bourse off course in its
assault on the 3,000 point milestone.
</P>
<P>
Another Macquarie Nevitts adviser Steve Mayne said that besides
Wall Street, the major influence on the local market Wednesday was
the gold price, which has fallen roughly 8.OO U.S. dollars an
ounce in two days.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index offloaded 27.8 points to 5,369.6,
while the all resources index dipped 2.8 points to 1,017.9.
</P>
<P>
The gold index retreated 13 points to 1,021.4.
</P>
<P>
The spot price of gold bullion in Sydney Wednesday afternoon
was 284.00 U.S. dollars an ounce, 2.00 U.S. dollars less than
Tuesday's 286.00 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the industrial sector, banks had a mixed day with the
industry sub-index easing 3.1 points to 7,000.5.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank slumped 40 cents to 28.09 Australian
dollars and Commonwealth Bank of Australia eased one cent to 25.77
Australian dollar, while Westpac bank stacked on 16 cents to 11.10
Australian dollars and ANZ bank climbed 17 cents to 11.16
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, Australia's biggest industrial company
BHP rose 14.5 cents to 12.74 Australian dollars, global miner Rio
Tinto slipped 22 cents to 22.03 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 357.23 million stocks traded for 675.75
million U.S. dollars. Falling stocks outnumbered rising stocks 724
to 491, while 475 stocks remained steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
