<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Egyptian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Egyptian newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Al-Akhbar:
</P>
<P>
-- Foreign Minister Amr Moussa leaves Cairo for Addis Ababa,
Ethiopia on Sunday to lead Egypt's delegation to the two-day 69th
session of the Ministerial Council of the Organization of African
Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
The session will cover a number of political and economic issues
of interest to Africa, and issues pertaining to disputes in the
continent and ways to activate the role of the OAU in this respect.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ahram:
</P>
<P>
-- Public Works and Water Resources Minister Mahmoud Zeid said
Egypt would offer a 13 million U.S. dollar grant for Uganda to
resist the Nile Lily and pollution at Kiowa Lake, the second
largest lake of seven lakes Uganda after Victoria lake.
</P>
<P>
Al-Gomhuria:
</P>
<P>
-- Tourism Minister Mamdouh Beltagui and Cairo governor Abdul
Rehim Shehata on Wednesday inaugurate the biggest tourist and
sports complex.
</P>
<P>
The complex which is established on 10,000 meters aims to
attract Arab and international investments to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Gazette:
</P>
<P>
-- Egypt on Tuesday reiterated its full support to all Arab
agricultural integration and cooperation programs that will
achieve food sufficiency in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture and Land Reclamation Minister Youssef Wali said
that the food sufficiency target could be only achieved through
the coordination of Arab agricultural plans and encouraging
inter-Arab trade and joint agricultural projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
