<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Announces Initiatives for Asset Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Monetary Authority of
Singapore (MAS) Wednesday announced new initiatives to attract
asset managers to use the city state as a regional center to
manage their Asian mandates as well as some global mandates.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the second annual conference of the Investment
Management Association of Singapore (IMAS), MAS Managing Director
Koh Yong Guan said MAS will this year focus on attracting
reputable foreign intermediaries in fixed income activities,
strengthening the local industry particularly by promoting
boutique fund managers and building up the skills pool in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
Koh said a key component of Singapore's strategy to develop the
debt capital market is to attract reputable global fixed income
trading and arrange teams to base their Asian operations in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
This will give asset managers a wide range of debt instruments
to invest in, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said asset managers should leverage on Singapore's
strength in foreign exchange and treasury operations and clients
who want to reduce portfolio risk through currency hedging or seek
enhanced returns through dynamic trading of currency exposures
will find such services attractive.
</P>
<P>
On strengthening the local industry, Koh said MAS will
introduce a streamlined licensing scheme with appropriate
incentives aimed at developing more boutique fund management firms
or BFMs.
</P>
<P>
These smaller firms owned and operated by experienced
professionals provide specialized investment and advisory services
to selected institutional and high net-worth individual clients,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that there are currently about a dozen BFMs in
Singapore, Koh said licensing them as investment advisers or IAs
will improve their ability to reach out to a wider client base.
</P>
<P>
He listed seven items of requirements for BFMs to qualify as
IAs and underlined that MAS has softened most of the terms.
</P>
<P>
MAS is also prepared to consider licensing foreign-owned BFMs
on a case-by-case basis if they have operated in Singapore either
as an approved fund manager or exempt IA for at least three years,
Koh added.
</P>
<P>
Emphasizing that the most critical success factor for
developing the asset management industry will be the ability to
build a broad and deep talent pool, Koh said MAS will exert itself
to ensure there is a ready supply of talents who have strong
academic qualifications in related disciplines and professional
qualifications like the Chartered Financial Analysts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
