<HEADLINE> Israeli Right-Wing Party Leader Convicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Aryeh Deri, leader of Israel's
powerful right-wing Shas Party, Wednesday was convicted of
bribe-taking by Jerusalem District Court.
</P>
<P>
Deri, a close associate of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu,
was also convicted of fraud and breaching public trust.
</P>
<P>
Judge Yaakov Tzemach announced the verdicts before reading a
917-page decision.
</P>
<P>
Although Deri was also acquitted on some other charges against
him, the bribery conviction would carry a maximum sentence of
seven year imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
It is still not clear when the sentencing will take place.
</P>
<P>
The Shas Party, which currently has 10 seats in the 120-member
Knesset (parliament), is made up of Jews with Middle Eastern
origin.
</P>
<P>
Since it is only less than two months before the general
elections of Israel, Deri's conviction is likely to raise
tensions in the country.
</P>
<P>
Some followers of Shas regarded the conviction as a ruling
against the whole party and threatened to hold mass
demonstration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
