<HEADLINE> Another Iraqi Plane Breaks Air Ban, Carries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Another Iraqi plane carrying 111
elderly pilgrims on Wednesday morning took off from Baghdad
heading for the holy city of Mecca in Saudi Arabia, where pilgrims
will perform rituals of hadj.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, an Iraqi plane carrying 110 elderly pilgrims also
took off from Baghdad for Mecca.
</P>
<P>
This is the third time that Iraq broke the United Nations air
ban imposed on the country after the 1991 Gulf War. In 1997, an
Iraqi plane carrying Iraq's elderly pilgrims flew to Jeddah
airport in southwestern Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, nearly 2,000 Iraqi pilgrims left for Saudi Arabia
for the hadj by buses, the first group from Iraq to perform the
annual Muslim pilgrimage to Mecca this year. On Tuesday, another
2,000 pilgrims left Baghdad for Mecca by buses.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, with a population of over 22 million, can send up to
22,000 pilgrims to Mecca under quotas set by the Organization of
the Islamic Conference.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions, which have impoverished most ordinary
Iraqis, have made it impossible for all but the wealthiest to
afford the pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Foreign Ministry on Sunday accused United States and
British representatives in the U.N. Sanctions Committee of
impeding efforts to try to help Iraqis perform their pilgrimage
by rejecting the Iraqi proposal for using its frozen assets in
foreign countries to finance its pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, 3,000 Iraqi pilgrims made the trip to Mecca to
perform hadj. In 1997, Iraq flew a planeload of pilgrims to
Mecca, other pilgrims were flown by helicopters to the
Iraqi-Saudi border despite a ban on flights over Iraq enforced by
the U.S. and Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
