<HEADLINE> South Korea Welcomes U.S.-DPRK Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 17 (Xinhua) -- South Korea Wednesday welcomed the
agreement signed between Washington and Pyongyang Tuesday in New
York which allows U.S. access to suspected underground nuclear
facilities in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
The government of the Republic of Korea "welcomes" the "
desirable settlement" reached at the fourth round of the U.S.-DPRK
negotiations over Kumchang-ni underground construction held from
February 27 to march 15, said the Ministry for Foreign Affairs and
Trade.
</P>
<P>
South Korea expects the DPRK to fully comply with the agreement,
thereby completely dispelling suspicion over Kumchang-ni site, It
said.
</P>
<P>
The nation also hopes the DPRK will leave no grounds for other
nuclear-related suspicions in the future by faithfully sticking
to various international norms and agreements, such as the "Joint
Declaration on the Denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula", "Non-
Proliferation Treaty", "IAEA Safeguards Agreement" and "1994
Framework Agreement," it said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement the DPRK will allow U.S. access to its
nuclear-suspected underground site in May this year and next year
and guarantees further access when necessary, while the United
States will supply the DPRK seeds, fertilizers and agricultural
technology.
</P>
<P>
The suspected nuclear Kumchang-ni site first became a focus of
international press last August after U.S. satellite photos linked
it to secret nuclear facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
