<HEADLINE> Russia Wants Better Economic Ties with U.S., Says Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov has called for better economic relations with the United
States, the Itar-Tass news agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral economic ties "are undoubtedly changing for the
better, but they are changing too slowly," Primakov said prior to
a visit to Washington to attend the session of the Russia-U.S.
economic cooperation commission on March 23-25.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States is among Russia's three largest
trading partners and trade turnover has been growing in the past
few years but the growth was not fast enough.
</P>
<P>
"What's 9 billion dollars a year compared with 1 billion
dollars per day in the U.S.-Canadian trade? What's 5 billion
dollars of U.S. investments in Russia compared with dozens,
perhaps hundreds of billions of dollars of U.S. investments in
China?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
"The present parameters of our economic relations are
unquestionably improving, but too slowly. We are facing hard and
painstaking work to strengthen the economic basis of the Russian-U.
S. partnership which looks into the 21st century," Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said during the upcoming U.S. visit, he
would try to re-orient the commission's work "to provide real
assistance to the solution of the problems faced by Russia."
</P>
<P>
Specifically, he would urge the Americans to drop anti-dumping
investigation into Russia's rolled steel exports, to expand the
quota for commercial space launched by Russian booster rockets and
to lift other discriminating and restrictive measures against
Russia.
</P>
<P>
"We also intend to thoroughly discuss with Americans possible
ways to boost contacts as regards small business, cooperation in
telecommunications and commercialization of technologies and
interaction in implementing a regional investment initiative,"
Primakov said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
