<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Israelis See PNA Genuine Peace Partner: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Most Israelis now believe the
Palestinian leadership is sincere in making peace with Israel,
while few of the Palestinians give much credit to the Israeli
government, a recent joint Israeli-Palestinian poll shows.
</P>
<P>
Also according to the poll, released here Wednesday, the two
peoples are divergent over the future of Jerusalem along a
clear-cut national line.
</P>
<P>
The poll results were submitted by Tel Aviv University's Tami
Sterinmetz Center for Peace (TSCP) and the Jerusalem Media and
Communication Center (JMCC) after querying 500 Israelis and 500
Palestinians respectively.
</P>
<P>
Some 41.7 percent of the Israelis interviewed think the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) is "genuine" in making peace
with Israel, anther 19.8 percent answered it's "very genuine."
</P>
<P>
By comparison with a 1997 poll on the same question, the
PNA's credibility is on the rise among the Israelis despite the
Israeli government's allegations of Palestinian non-compliance
with peace deals.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 poll showed 14.4 percent of the Israelis thought the
PNA to be "very genuine" while 37.9 percent found it "genuine."
</P>
<P>
Tamar Hermann, director of the TSCP, attributed the growing
confidence in the PNA to a sustained period without terrorist
attacks inside the Green Line, or Cease-fire Line of the 1967
Middle East War.
</P>
<P>
It has to do with an increased sense of personal security and
the Israelis gave the PNA credit for curbing terrorist attacks,
Tamar said.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians, by contrast, overwhelmingly distrust the
intentions of the Israeli government towards the peace process,
according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
Some 52.5 percent of the Palestinians termed its intentions
"not genuine at all," while 36.3 percent described it "not
genuine."
</P>
<P>
The poll also showed that most Israelis believe the post-Oslo
peace process will result in the establishment of a "genuinely
independent Palestinian state," with 33.5 percent saying this will
"surely happen" while 39.6 percent believe it will "probably
happen."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 64.7 percent of the Israeli respondents disagree
with the establishment of a Palestinian state comprising the West
Bank and Gaza Strip and with East Jerusalem as its capital, with
only 17.4 percent supporting this idea, 12.9 percent observing
neutrality and 5 percent saying they don't known.
</P>
<P>
However, 91.3 percent of the Palestinian respondents said no to
accepting Jerusalem as the "unified capital of Israel" as a
bargain to break a final deadlock in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The poll was sponsored by the People to People program, a
Norwegian effort to promote Israeli-Palestinian contact as part
of the Oslo Accords signed in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
