<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Auto Industry Growth to Slow Down: Analysts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- China's auto industry will
continue to grow this year, but at a much lower speed, according
to today's China Consumer Journal.
</P>
<P>
Demand for automobiles will be further diversified and the
industry will see fiercer competition this year, local analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of the industry will be lower than that of the
GDP this year, as it was in 1998, they said.
</P>
<P>
Some 1.63 million automobiles were manufactured in China last
year, up 2.44 percent on an annual basis, as compared with the 7.8
percent growth of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute the slowdown to a weak domestic market and
restrictions imposed on individual car buyers in some regions.
They pointed out that many flood-hit provinces have listed
reconstruction as their top priority, crowding out potential car
purchases.
</P>
<P>
Expensive cars and limousines, which have accounted for half of
all auto sales in the past, will undergo a decline in demand as
the government is reducing the number of cars for official
purposes.
</P>
<P>
Sales of private cars are expected to grow by 10 percent, but
this growth rate is subject to changes in related policies and the
income of potential buyers, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
However, more buses and trucks are expected to be sold as huge
investments in infrastructure construction are taking effect. In
any case, the market share of trucks and buses is too small to
exert a significant influence on the auto industry overall.
</P>
</TEXT>
