<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Fuel Imports Rise by 12% </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The National Fuel Committee
of Ethiopia has said the amount of petroleum imports has increased
by 12 percent after the country started utilizing the port of
Djibouti in May last year, local English weekly "the Reporter"
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The weekly newspaper quoted Haile Assegide, chairman of the
board of the committee as saying that Ethiopia was previously
importing 80-85 million liters of petroleum per month while using
the Assab port, while it is now importing 100 million liters a
month.
</P>
<P>
Haile said the country previously was keeping very low amount
of petroleum in reserve which could last only a few days.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, with the view of reserving petroleum that
would be consumed for months, the government had embarked upon the
construction of petroleum depots in different parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
After listing construction of petroleum depots in different
parts of the country, the board chairman said these depots are
expected to reserve petroleum that would meet more than 90 percent
of the country's demand for petroleum for three months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
