<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 08:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Gulf, A Long-term Weapons Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- With the oil price slump
hitting the incomes of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states,
many analysts predict that this year's International Defense
Exhibition (IDEX '99) may not end with large contracts.
</P>
<P>
The prediction is apparently well-based. The oil prices, down
by about 40 percent over the last 12 months, have hit the GCC
countries badly, for oil accounts for at least 70 percent of the
earnings in all of the GCC states but Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
The decline of oil incomes may curb the GCC states' defense
spending in the short term, as conventional wisdom dictates. But,
as the factors that stimulate defense spending still exist, the
region's weapons market will remain large in the long term.
</P>
<P>
Defense spending is essentially decided by the threats that a
country thinks exist. As long as tensions and supposed threats
exist, defense spending will remain large.
</P>
<P>
The outbreak of the Gulf War in 1991, caused by Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein's ill-devised military expedition into Kuwait, put
GCC countries into endless worries about their security, which in
turn spurred them to launch ambitious defense programs.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait, the victim of Iraqi invasion, has moved at a greater
pace than any of its neighbors, spending more than 8 billion
dollars procuring weapons and equipment since the end of the Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Oman, Qatar and Bahrain
all have been moving quickly to make their armed forces strong,
acquiring huge amounts of military hardware from the U.S.,
Britain, France and a variety of other exporters.
</P>
<P>
Now with the U.S. and British warplanes striking Iraq almost on
a daily basis, the tensions in the Gulf are not relaxed at all.
</P>
<P>
Iran's dispute with the UAE over the Gulf islands of Abu Mousa
and Greater and Lesser Tunbs only adds to the tensions. The UAE
has protested many times against Iran's "provocative" moves on or
near the islands.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has stressed that the ongoing IDEX '99 has nothing to
do with tensions in the region. This may be true, for the event is
held bi-annually. But, as all big defense companies see, the Gulf
has been and will remain a huge weapons market, which has much to
do with the region's situation.
</P>
<P>
The low oil prices may cause a slowdown in the Gulf's military
equipment purchases in the next three to four years, but after
that, the situation will improve, according to Alan Patterson, an
official of the British Ministry of Defense.
</P>
<P>
His view was echoed by defense officials of other important
countries attending IDEX '99.
</P>
<P>
New orders may not be placed by many of the Gulf countries but
existing orders have not been canceled, they said.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the U.S., France, Britain, Italgations from some 80 countries.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
