<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Movie "Mulan" Fails to Stir "Titanic" Wave in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A foreign-looking Hua Mulan, the
leading character in Walt Disney's cartoon movie "Mulan" based on
a Chinese folk story, has failed to attract as many moviegoers as
anticipated in the heroine's home country since the movie was
premiered in late February.
</P>
<P>
Hua Mulan is a legendary figure who joined the army in place
of her old and sick father during the Sui Dynasty, 1,300 years ago.
Nobody guessed she was female until the war ended because she
disguised herself as a man. Hua Mulan was later hailed as a great
warrior for her brilliant achievements.
</P>
<P>
As it closed yesterday in cinemas in central China's Hunan
Province, local box-office sales barely reached 250,000 yuan, only
half the income generated by another Hollywood hit movie called "
Rush Hour" starring Jackie Chan of Hong Kong, which was released
simultaneously in the province.
</P>
<P>
But neither film was a match for Hollywood's "Titanic" which
sailed into China last year and came away with 8 million yuan in
Hunan alone.
</P>
<P>
"Mulan" also had bad luck in the southern province of Guangdong
and in Shanghai, China's most bustling city with a population of
over 14 million. Only 200,000 people in Shanghai went to see "
Mulan," and barely 2 million yuan was taken in at the box office.
</P>
<P>
"It is far from what we had expected," said one official of the
municipal movie-distribution company.
</P>
<P>
He cited an unfavorable release time as one reason for the
movie's flop. "Mulan" debuted on February 23 in Shanghai just as
the new school semester was about to start. This prevented many
young people and their parents from going to see it, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, people in Hunan hold different views. One viewer in
Changsha, the provincial capital, said that the Disney version of
Hua Mulan is completely different from the story the Chinese learn
through poems and folk stories, and that her complexion,
disposition and manner of behavior were different.
</P>
<P>
One movie commentator claimed that it is all right for a
cartoon movie to have its distinct interpretation of characters,
but the problem is that Chinese children might be more familiar
with and interested in such Disney figures as Mickey Mouse than
the legendary Chinese heroine.
</P>
<P>
She added that generally speaking, cartoon pictures lack appeal
to adult Chinese audiences.
</P>
<P>
Some movie industry insiders say that the fact that "Mulan" was
successful in the United States but apparently failed in her
homeland, indicates that China had better make use of its own
abundant cultural resources to instill traditions in the younger
generation.
</P>
<P>
The movie is set for an April 14 release in Beijing, but
considering its reception in other parts of China so far, it is
unlikely to do well there either. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Private Enterprises In Ningbo Development Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The number of private
enterprises in the development zone of Ningbo, a coastal city in
east China's Zhejiang Province, has topped 1,000.
</P>
<P>
The enterprises have a total registered capital of 1.2 billion
yuan, thanks to the introduction of a series of flexible policies.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-six new private enterprises opened in the zone in
January and 16 more were set up in February, more than twice as
many as in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Private enterprises are allowed to register locally without
any limitations placed on business scope, size, or expansion speed.
</P>
<P>
Private businesses in the zone paid 60 million yuan in taxes
last year and earned 130 million yuan in foreign exchange from
exports.
</P>
<P>
As one of the earliest state-level development zones, the 15-
year-old Ningbo Development Zone now has 442 overseas-funded
enterprises using capital from 30 countries and regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
