<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seminar on U.N. Peacekeeping Opens in New Delhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- An international seminar on
U.N. peacekeeping operations opened here Wednesday with India
calling on certain countries to pay their arrears to the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
Indian Minister of State for External Affairs Vasundhara Raje
said at the opening ceremony that the United Nations has been
facing an acute financial crisis created by the reluctance of some
countries to pay their assessed contribution.
</P>
<P>
India believes that assessed contributions are a treaty
obligation and must be paid in full on time and without
preconditions, Raje told the seminar, which is being jointly held
by the ministries of external affairs and defense.
</P>
<P>
The world has witnessed instability, war and ethnic strife not
only in Asia and Africa, but also in Europe while the U.N.
peacekeeping budget had been reduced to less than one-third of the
level a few years ago, said Raje.
</P>
<P>
She also called for reform and expansion of the U.N. Security
Council, which sets the mandate for peacekeeping operations.
</P>
<P>
Over the years, India provided a total of 50,000 troops to 29
peacekeeping operations, some of which in most risky areas
including Egypt, Congo, Cambodia, Somalia and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Young-Jin Choi, U.N. assistant secretary general in charge of
U.N. peacekeeping operations, gave an overview of U.N.
peacekeeping activities around the world.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day seminar, delegates will discuss
peacekeeping operations and experiences in Africa, international
humanitarian law and U.N. peacekeeping, India's experience in
peacekeeping, and leadership and management of senior commanders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
