<HEADLINE> Coles Leaves "Dead Cat" on Table at SOCOG, Says Board Member  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The refusal of Australia's
International Olympic Committee (IOC) member Phil Coles to step
down from the Sydney Olympics organizing board had left SOCOG with
"a dead cat on the table," a fellow board member said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ron Phillips, the New South Wales state opposition spokesman on
the Olympics, joined several board members in urging Coles to quit
from his role with the 2000 Games.
</P>
<P>
Coles has been investigated by the IOC for accepting bribery
from Salt Lake City during its bid to host the 2002 Winter
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Coles, 67, quit his position in the Australian Olympic
Committee last week citing health reasons. But he cannot be
sacked from the SOCOG board as the its contract with the IOC
stipulates that all Australian IOC members should be on the board.
</P>
<P>
"A dead cat has landed on the table of the SOCOG board and the
problem is going to remain while Phil Coles hangs around,"
Phillips said. "There is no doubt the feeling is that Phil Coles
remaining on the board diminishes the standing of SOCOG and the
Sydney Olympics in the eyes of the community." 
</P>
</TEXT>
