<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Witnesses Recovering Steel Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The demand for steel in Shanghai
has exhibited signs of recovery since the beginning of this month
along with increasing investment, according to one market analyst.
</P>
<P>
Tao Yonggen, a analyst for the East China Steel Market, said
the slow but positive recovery has been apparent since the
beginning of March, adding that sales of all types of steel
products have rebounded during the month.
</P>
<P>
The Baoshan Iron and Steel Company, a leading steel complex of
the country, sold 1,100 tons of seamless steel tubing over a 10
day period early this month, said Tao.
</P>
<P>
growing sales have also sparked rising steel prices, according
to Tao. He noted that threaded steel with a diameter of 25 mm is
currently selling at around 2,030 yuan per ton, up by some 30 yuan
on the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute the recovery in steel demand to the effects
of the proactive fiscal policy and peak production season for
appliances.
</P>
<P>
However, experts note that the structural overproduction of
steel has not as yet been rectified and therefore the current
recovery will most likely be limited.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to restructure the steel sector should be continued in
order to prevent a new round of overproduction, according to
experts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
