<HEADLINE> 13 Lebanese Charged With Spying for Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Eleven Lebanese men and two women
have been charged with spying for Israel, the Daily Star reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Assistant military prosecutor Myassar Shokor said they were
believed to have been recruited by Israeli intelligence to
collect information on Lebanese, Syrian military forces and
Palestinian leftist groups, the paper quoted judicial sources as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Shokor has requested sentences from three to 15 years in
prison with hard labor, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The group was uncovered after the arrest and interrogation of
an officer of the pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army last month.
</P>
<P>
The officer, Mohammed Khalil Nabaa, was responsible for
security in the village of Shebaa in the western sector of the
Israeli occupied border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He is believed to have spied on a Palestinian military group in
Lebanon and facilitated the arrest of some of the group's fighters.
</P>
<P>
Some of the 13 arrested are also suspected of selling drugs to
Israeli troops inside the border zone and smuggling European and
U.S.-made cigarettes into Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the self-proclaimed security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
