<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greater Hinggan Mountains Zone Declares Fire Alert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Greater Hinggan Mountains
Forest Zone in the northeast China declared on spring fire alert
beginning on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Fire control personnel have been posted at strategic locations
to inspect all visitors and motor vehicles. The alert bans the use
of cigarettes, matches and lighters, and motor vehicle operators
are required to cover exhaust pipes.
</P>
<P>
Members of the China Forest Police unit stationed in the
Greater Hinggan Mountains are fully prepared to take emergency
action.
</P>
<P>
The China Central Meteorological Observatory forecasts a 30
percent decrease in precipitation in the Greater Hinggan Mountains
since the spring period set in early this year compared to the
same period in previous years. Forecasts also call for higher
temperatures between April-June, and strong breezed over a 32 day
period are expected to increase the risk of fire.
</P>
<P>
Local administrative departments in the zone are preparing
against any possible forest fires along the border regions with
Mongolia and Russia. The departments have introduced a program to
enhance the fire prevention awareness of local residents and
closed illegal operations in the forest zone.
</P>
<P>
The National Forestry Administration has dispatched an
inspection group to help improve supervision and inspections of
fire prevention activities.
</P>
<P>
Local sources indicate the alert will be lifted by mid-June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
