<HEADLINE> China's Largest Desert Becomes More Moist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Taklimakan Desert, China's
largest, in the northwestern Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region is
turning warmer and moister, while the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau is
being more frequented by snowstorms due to global climatic changes,
according to a recent report in the Science Times newspaper.
</P>
<P>
A recent study by Chinese meteorologists shows that the
temperature in the northern Xinjiang is rising by 0.6 degrees
Celsius every year on average, while the temperature in the
southern region has risen 0.3 degrees Celsius yearly over the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
The winter in the region has also become shorter, and the
annual rainfall in the northern area has increased by 18 percent
and in the south by more than 30 percent over the past ten years.
</P>
<P>
The Taklimakan Desert, often called the "sea of death," has
been experiencing more rainfall over recent years, and satellite
sensors indicate that some transient lakes have been appearing in
the desert.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, global climatic changes have also brought more
snowstorms to the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, and the snows there in
the 1990s were twice as heavy as they were in the 1960s, according
to the article. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
