<HEADLINE> Zambia Red Cross Allowed to Assess Refugee's Camps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Red Cross Society (ZRCS)
has been given the mandate to assess proposed areas of settlement
for the military and civilian refugees who have flooded into the
country as war escalates in the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC).
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's Times of Zambia newspaper quoted ZRCS as saying
hundreds of Congolese refugees fleeing into Zambia through Kaputa
in Northern Province are living in open countryside with neither
shelter nor facilities.
</P>
<P>
"The majority of the new arrivals are located at reception
center at a partially-built school in the town area but many
others are surviving in the open countryside," ZRCS spokesman
Kampata Banda said in Lusaka Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Official reports indicate an influx into Zambia of about 2,000
refugees including at least 750 DRC government soldiers from the
DRC towns of Pepo and Pweto after a rebel offensive.
</P>
<P>
Banda said ZRCS was selected to manage refugee camps in
accordance with the contingency plan established by the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and other agencies.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR had asked ZRCS to provide assistance in asserting the
 suitability of new refugee camp sites near Kasama and Mporokoso
following the latest influx of refugees into Kaputa, he said.
</P>
<P>
Banda said the International Federation of Red Cross Societies
(IFRC) had provided funds to ZRCS to enable it to mobilize and
deploy an emergency team from headquarters in Kaputa.
</P>
<P>
"The emergency team consisting four senior staff is currently
in Kaputa area and is being assisted in their work by a water and
sanitation program officer sent by the IFRC," he said.  
</P>
