<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Growth of Marriage to Foreigners Slows Down in Qingdao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The increase of marriage to
foreigners and overseas Chinese has slowed down in Qingdao, a
coastal port city in east China's Shandong Province, in recent
years in contrast with a boom during the early nineties.
</P>
<P>
The number of residents in the city who married foreigners and
overseas Chinese last year grew three percentage points less than
in 1997, according to the local civil affairs bureau.
</P>
<P>
While foreigners and overseas Chinese seem to be losing favor
with local residents, marriages involving overseas people have
gains in quality as the difference in age between husbands and
wives has become less dramatic than before.
</P>
<P>
In more than half of the marriages last year, the age gap was
reduced to no more than ten years, and it was rare to see a young
woman going to register a marriage with a man twice her age.
</P>
<P>
Two-thirds of the couples got married after they had known each
other for more than one year, up about 30 percent from previous
years.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute the changes to the fact that fewer local
residents view marriage as the pathway to a better life or a way
to see the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Marriages to foreigners and overseas Chinese began again after
1978, when China started its reforms and opening up to the outside
world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0242 </DOCNO>
