<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malnutrition Lowers South China Tiger's Fertility Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Tigers in south China zoos are
suffering malnutrition as a result of poor food quality which, say
experts, is slowly lowering their fertility rate and damaging
their health.
</P>
<P>
An international symposium was recently informed that two
surveys in 1995 and 1997 on four zoos in China showed that the
fourteen South China tigers there are provided with raw meat
instead of small, live animals and eggs. Most of meat is too lean
and the additives affect the tigers digestive systems.
</P>
<P>
"The food we give to tigers does not have enough nutritional
value, and this has resulted in the decline of their health and a
lower fertility rate," said Xie Zhong, secretary-general of the
Chinese Association of Zoos.
</P>
<P>
She revealed that the 56 South China tigers in captivity in 22
Chinese zoos are the only ones in the world. They belong to one of
the ten major endangered species listed by international
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The inbreeding and caging of tigers are other factors which
hinder the development of the species. A survey on eight male
South China tigers in 1997 showed that two could not produce any
semen, one has inactive sperm and most of the other five have a
lower sperm quality than normal.
</P>
<P>
In a bit to protect the species, China has established a
special committee to coordinate protective measures and has
established a gene bank for the South China Tiger.
</P>
<P>
The gene bank in Shanghai will use semen for future artificial
insemination, and stores samples of tiger cells, hair and blood
for research purposes.
</P>
<P>
Now the Chongqing Zoo plans to build a special tiger country-
style sanctuary, dozens of times larger than the original
dwellings for its four tigers.
</P>
<P>
Last October, the State Forestry Administration established a
South China Tiger nature reserve in Fujian Province and moved five
tigers there to enjoy a wilder living environment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
