<HEADLINE> Moderate Earthquake Hits Areas Near Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake hit the Sydney
region Wednesday, cutting power to more than 2,000 homes, shutting
down mines and jamming emergency switchboards, the Australian
Broadcasting Corporation reported.
</P>
<P>
There were no reports of casualties yet.
</P>
<P>
Seismologists said more earthquakes are expected over the next
few weeks following Wednesday's tremor, which was the second
within a week in New South Wales (NSW), whose capital is Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's quake measured 4.7 on the Richter scale and was
felt up to 200 km from the epicenter, which was about 5 km south
of Appin, in Sydney's south-west.
</P>
<P>
About 2,200 homes and businesses in Appin and Camden, about 60
km from Sydney, were without power for up to 90 minutes following
the earthquake at 12.58 p.m., Australian Eastern Daylight Time
(AEDT).
</P>
<P>
Emergency service organizations were flooded with calls from
across Sydney, while several coal mines in the local area were
temporarily evacuated in case of a collapse.
</P>
<P>
Kevin McCue, a seismologist with the Australian Geological
Survey Organization, was quoted by the Australian Associated Press
as saying he believed a series of earthquakes would hit Sydney
over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
An earthquake measuring 4.2 on the Richter scale was recorded
in West Wyalong, in central NSW, at 11.13 a.m. AEDT Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"It is a fact of life that earthquakes occur in swarms. There
may be four, or five, or six occurring within days or weeks,"
McCue said.
</P>
<P>
"I would not be surprised if a couple more earthquakes occurred
in NSW or (the neighboring state) Victoria over the next few
weeks". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
