<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, U.S. Firm Sign Accord for Power Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh and a United
States-based corporation have signed a 280-million U.S. dollar
power purchasing agreement for the proposed 450-megwatt Meghnaghat
Combined Cycle Power Plant, press reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year agreement was signed between the Bangladesh Power
Development Board (BPDB) and the AES Corporation in Dhaka Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the pact, the AES Corporation will invest about 280
million dollars for the gas-run power plant to be set up at
Meghnaghat, 20 kilometers southeast of Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
The proposed Meghnaghat power plant, which will be the single
largest power project in the country, will be developed by a
private developer on the "build-own-operate" basis.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have to reach understanding on three more agreements
including implementation, fuel supply and the land leasing,
according to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
During the whole period, the BPDB would have to purchase all
electricity generated from the project.
</P>
<P>
After the signing of all the final agreements, the private
developer would have to complete its financial closure within six
months and the plant would have to be in operation within the next
30 months.
</P>
<P>
In case of failure on the part of the private developer, the
BPDB would be in a position to charge penalty at 45,000 dollars
per day.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, if the BPDB fails to take the electricity,
it would have to pay capacity charges to the private developer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
