<HEADLINE> Interview: President Jiang's Swiss Visit a Milestone (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Switzerland's ambassador to China,
Dominique Dreyer, said Chinese President Jiang Zemin's first ever
state visit to his country will be the most important event since
the two nations established their bilateral diplomatic ties in
1950.
</P>
<P>
Dreyer is a veteran diplomat who has been involved in Sino-
Swiss relations ever since the 1970s. He acknowledged that
Switzerland was among the first group of the Western countries to
recognize New China.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that this visit will be crowned with a success
and be a milestone in bilateral relations," said Dreyer.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang will pay a three-day visit to Switzerland,
later this month, traveling to the Swiss capital of Bern, Geneva,
a financial and banking center, and Basel, a leading industrial
city in the north.
</P>
<P>
He will hold talks with Ruth Dreifuss, president of the Swiss
Confederation, and meet with personages from all walks of life in
Switzerland, especially those from business circles. Moreover,
according to Dreyer, cooperative agreements in the fields of
culture, education, economics and environmental protection are
expected to be signed.
</P>
<P>
As for the present Sino-Swiss economic and trade relations,
Dreyer said that the trade volumes have shown a growing trend in
recent years despite the effect to some extent of the Asian
financial crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: President Jiang's Swiss Visit a Milestone (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On Swiss-Chinese economic and trade relations, Dreyer said he
held that China and Switzerland have great potential for increased
trade cooperation, noting that more than 400 Swiss companies are
already involved in China including the giant ABB Company. He also
predicts that the two countries will confirm further cooperation
in particular with machine building sector and environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
"Switzerland is well known for its sophisticated technology in
the fields of industry, banking business and environmental
protection but China has probably the biggest potential market in
the world," added Dreyer, who expressed the belief that boosting
bilateral economic cooperation will help herald a new stage in
China's own economic development.
</P>
<P>
After analyzing the basic reason for Switzerland and China to
enjoying friendly relations for the past 50 years, Dreyer noted
that the two countries are peace-loving nations and their peoples
cherish profound feelings for friendship for each other. And there
are essentially no clash of fundamental interests between the two
nations.
</P>
<P>
"Over these long years, in recent years in particular, the
continuing exchange of visits between high-level officials has
enabled the relations between the two countries to become closer
still," said Dreyer, who also witnessed that as a result of the
dramatic changes taking place in China over the past two decades
its people are now more pragmatic and open-minded than in the past.
</P>
<P>
As a Swiss ambassador, he said he would encourage more Swiss
people to visit China or come to study the country on a business
tour while extending a greeting to any Chinese people keen to
travel to his beautiful country, which he believes will in turn
further increase mutual understanding and promote bilateral
relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
