<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cloud-seeding to Ease Drought In Shandong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Tuesday cloud-seeding efforts
carried to induce rainfall are expected to ease the drought
affecting 2.35 million ha of farmland in east China's Shandong
Province, one of China's major grain producers.
</P>
<P>
Yesterday's operation involving one aircraft brought light
overnight precipitation to five cities and prefectures, including
Jinan, the provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
Tonight's operation involving two aircraft is expected to bring
even more rainfall, according to the Jinan Cloud-seeding Office.
</P>
<P>
The province, located in the lower reaches of the Yellow River,
China's second longest river, has been in the grips of a rare
drought since early spring. The drought conditions have increased
pollution caused by wastewater discharges in the upper and middle
reaches of the river.
</P>
<P>
One waterworks along the river was forced to close in January.
</P>
<P>
However, urban residents and factories along the river do not
as yet face a water shortage due to the fact that the storage
capacity of local reservoirs is up by 2.47 billion cu.m. on last
year's level.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
