<HEADLINE> Dhaka Expected to Earn 1.43 Bln Dollars From Manpower Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Remittances by Bangladeshis working
abroad are expected to stand at 70 billion taka (1.43 billion U.S.
dollars) this year as against 60 billion taka (1.24 billion
dollars) last year, the New Nation daily newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The projected increase excludes remittances coming unofficially
from expatriate Bangladeshis working in different countries, a
senior official of the Department of Manpower was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Manpower export from this South Asian country is likely to rise
to 165,000 in 1999 as against 158,000 last year, he predicts.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh mainly exports unskilled manpower to almost all the
countries in the Middle East specially the Gulf states besides
Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
There is also a bright prospect for export of skilled manpower
to Singapore where 25,000 to 30,000 Bangladeshis are now working,
he said.
</P>
<P>
There is scope for export of 7,000 trained and skilled workers
per year to take up employment in the emerging shipbuilding
industry in Singapore, he said, adding that a joint venture
training center has been set up in Sava, about 40 km west of
Dhaka, to equip manpower with shipbuilding skill for foreign
employment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bangladesh will explore manpower markets in South
Africa, Botswana, Madagascar and Brunei in the immediate future,
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
