<HEADLINE> Landslide Occurs In Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, March 17 (Xinhua) -- All the people injured in a
recent landslide in northwest China's Gansu Province are out of
danger, a hospital official said here today.
</P>
<P>
A national highway, which was cut off by the landslide, has
also reopened.
</P>
<P>
The landslide occurred in the morning of March 12 at a village
in Yongjing County, killing two people. It damaged almost all the
houses in Jiaojia Village and engulfed three township-run
enterprises and 5.3 ha of farmland. A section of a highway road
was covered with 100,000 cubic meters of stone and earth with a
width of 50 meters.
</P>
<P>
A local government official estimated the direct economic
losses at 5 million yuan. Experts say they have now assembled
essential data for the cause of the landslide and are
investigating.
</P>
<P>
Recalling the terrible scene, Jiao Xianglian, a female villager,
said, "When I saw large chunks of rock tumbling from the Heitai
Mountain on March 12, I ran along the road and cried: 'Landslide,
landslide'."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jiao Shifu, an electrical welder of Huaxin Carbofrax
Plant, said, "I saw a huge mound of earth covering part of our
plant, ruining the factory entrance gate and walls and turning
over five furnaces."  
</P>
</TEXT>
