<HEADLINE> TV Play Featuring Old-Age Romance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, March 17 (Xinhua) -- An 18-part TV comedy featuring
old-age romance in China will soon be screened by China Central
Television (CCTV) and more than 100 local television stations
across the country.
</P>
<P>
In China, old-age romance had long remained a taboo for people
who had lost their spouses and looking for new spouses was usually
considered indecent.
</P>
<P>
Centering on retired comedian Wang Xiliang, who is a widower,
the TV drama retells romantic stories of five old people who have
all lost their spouses and presents a lively modern-life episode
through the confrontation between modern civilization and out-
dated concepts, as well as disputes between old and young people.
</P>
<P>
Entitled "Evening Sunlight Is Not A Dream", the TV series is a
joint production between the Liaoning Provincial Video and Audio
Publishing House, the TV branch of Changchun Film Studio and CCTV.
</P>
<P>
The TV series is aimed at marking 1999 as the International
Year of Older Persons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
