<HEADLINE> China to Tap Potential in African News Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- China's media organizations,
especially the Xinhua News Agency, have great potential and bright
prospects in exploring the news market in Africa, a populous
continent with a large market for news, said Alhaji Wada Maida,
visiting managing director of the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN),
here today in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Maida pointed out that sound political and economic cooperation
and the traditional friendship between the African countries and
China are to Xinhua's advantage if the agency wants to expand its
operations on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua and NAN signed an agreement on the exchange of news
services in 1987, which allowed NAN, the state news agency of
Nigeria, to directly receive Xinhua's news through satellite. In
1998, the two agencies also agreed that NAN will help Xinhua to
increase subscribers in Nigeria, laying the foundation for further
cooperation between the two agencies.
</P>
<P>
Maida expressed his satisfaction with the cooperation between
the two agencies, saying that NAN uses many news items from Xinhua
everyday, because "Xinhua's news releases are of high quality in
terms of efficiency, range of coverage and information value, and
Xinhua can also stand with and serve the interests of the
developing countries."
</P>
<P>
"Due to the traditional African-Chinese friendship, almost all
African people regard China as a reliable old friend. Therefore,
they believe in Xinhua's reports, and regard them as authentic."
</P>
<P>
Maida has the ambition to turn NAN into a modernized news
agency. He made the trip to China to learn from Xinhua's
experiences in the process of modernization, and agreed with Guo
Chaoren, president of Xinhua, that the two sides should further
bilateral cooperation in the fields of news photography and
economic information.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1976, NAN is based in Abujia, the capital of
Nigeria, and has a principal office in the coastal city of Lagos
and 35 state and 38 district offices, as well as four foreign
bureaus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
