<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tax Reduction Unlikely in Near Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Experts have ruled out the
possibility of tax-reduction in the near future as a remedy to
spur up the Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
Quoted by today's Economic Information Daily they said that
due to a complicated taxation structure, there is limited choice
for China to reduce taxes like many other countries.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that at present China's general tax burden has
just reached the world's medium level.
</P>
<P>
They also pointed out that it is unrealistic for China to adopt
a low-tax-rate system since the country, on its way towards
industrialization, is in urgent need of funds.
</P>
<P>
While reducing taxes can weaken the government's financial
strength, it may not be very effective in stimulating the economy,
since for many loss making enterprises, tax-reduction only means a
decrease in the amount of tax default, they observed.
</P>
<P>
They also said that a more realistic and urgent act would be to
reduce the enterprises' and farmers' heavy burdens caused by
irrational levies of fees by governments at various levels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Needs 4,000 Actuaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- There is only one qualified
actuary in China, while the country's insurance market will need
some 4,000 actuaries in the near future, according to the China
Insurance Association.
</P>
<P>
Pan Lufu vice president of the association, was quoted in
Wednesday's China Economic Times as saying that China now has
around 40 "quasi-actuaries," or semi-qualified people, in addition
to the one qualified actuary among its 1.2 billion population.
</P>
<P>
An actuary is a specialist who calculates statistical risks,
premiums, and other factors related to the insurance industry, and
insurance companies are required to have at least one qualified
actuary and a system to report its actuarial work, according to
China's insurance regulations.
</P>
<P>
To be a qualified actuary, one must master mathematics,
statistics, economics, and investment science and have some
expertise in insurance. The country is now in great need of such
personnel.
</P>
<P>
More importance is now being given to the training of qualified
actuaries, Pan said, adding that nine graduate students at the
Central University of Finance and Economics have recently earned
master's degrees in actuarial studies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Women Benefit from Sterilization Reversal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Sterilized women in China now
have the opportunity to have the operation reversed, if the
circumstances are acceptable.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the Shanghai No. 9 People's
Hospital has so far performed the operation on more than 3,000
sterilized women since it was first introduced in China in 1981.
</P>
<P>
An example of how the reversal can be of huge benefit is Xu
Jinmei, a formerly sterilized woman in east China's Jiangsu
Province. She suffered great pain since she lost her only son in
an accident. Fortunately she became pregnant after having the
skilled operation in Shanghai and now has pretty twins to comfort
her.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to improving medical techniques, the Shanghai hospital
has achieved a 100 percent success rate in the reversal procedure,
and 95 percent of women have later had another child.
</P>
<P>
As many as 160 million women in the world are estimated to seek
sterilization, tens millions of them are in China, as part of
family planning measures.
</P>
<P>
Medical experts say that the majority of couples who lose their
children from whatever cause later suffer from depression and the
operation can help them solve the problem.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
