<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Regards China as Important Dialogue Partner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) has always regarded China as an important
dialogue partner given its tremendous economic capacity, a
Malaysian official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This was because China's huge economic capacity could actually
contribute toward the ASEAN's economic progress and development,
Malaysia's Deputy Minister of Science, Technology and Environment
Datuk Abu Bakar Daud said at the opening of the second meeting of
the ASEAN-China Joint Cooperation Committee (ACJCC) here.
</P>
<P>
He said the ASEAN, which has extensive trade and investment
linkages with China, would like to see an economically stable
China.
</P>
<P>
"We in ASEAN wish to see China succeed in its efforts to
resolve the economic problems facing the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Abu Bakar expressed the ASEAN's appreciation of China's action
and economic measures aimed at assisting ASEAN members to recover
from the economic crisis and hoped that it will continue with its
effort.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN welcomes China's assurances not to devalue its
currency, the renminbi, despite tremendous pressure from several
parties, he said.
</P>
<P>
"While emphasis is being given in promoting economic
cooperation, equally important is the need to strengthen political
ties between ASEAN and China," Abu Bakar said.
</P>
<P>
He lauded consultations between China and the ASEAN through the
ASEAN Nine Plus Three (China, Japan and South Korea), Post
Ministerial Conferences (PMC) and the ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF).
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting will focus on the review of the
implementation of projects approved by the first meeting in
Beijing, China, in 1997, which include the Economic and Trade
Seminar and the Officials Exchange Program between the ASEAN and
China.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also revise and exchange views on the
cooperation between the ASEAN and China toward the new millennium
and study and approve a number of projects to be implemented under
the ASEAN-China Cooperation Fund.
</P>
<P>
It will discuss proposals to address the financial and economic
crisis that has spread in the ASEAN region and East Asia since
July 1997 and sought China's commitment to undertaking actions and
new policies to reduce the problem.
</P>
<P>
China's Assistant Foreign Minister Wang Yi is leading the
Chinese delegation at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Wang said at the opening that assurances by China's President
Jiang Zemin not to devalue the renminbi truly reflects the
country's commitment to helping its ASEAN neighbors during the
financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
"His (Jiang's) words demonstrate China's responsibility to hold
the renminbi stable so as to make contributions to the economies
in Asia and the world at large," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
