<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet Okays Budget for Pollution Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet has approved a
5.7-billion-baht (154 million U.S. dollars) budget for 24
pollution-control projects under the National Economic and Social
Development Board's green fund package.
</P>
<P>
A government house news release available here Wednesday said
the amount comprises a 4-billion-baht (108 million dollars) loan
from Japan's Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund and 1.7 billion
baht (45.9 million dollars) from the annual budget.
</P>
<P>
All the 24 approved projects cover the period from 1999 to
2001, and relate to garbage treatment facilities, waste-water
treatment plants and air pollution-control facilities.
</P>
<P>
Priority is given to the pollution-control zone and provinces
which have serious environmental problems, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the 24 projects has been developed over the
past few years, but only 38.9 percent of the approved budget, or
3.88 billion baht (104.8 million dollars) out of a total of 9.97
billion baht (269.4 million dollars), has been spent due to
technical reasons.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet, therefore, asked the Office of Environmental
Policy and Planning to speed up the payment of the budget and
project construction to hasten the investment payback from the
pollution treatment fee of those projects.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet has also assigned the Science Ministry as
consultant for the local authorities in applying and processing
the projects, including helping to study the pollution treatment
charge rate, in accordance with the polluter-pay principle in the
1992 Environment Act. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
