<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, March 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
WASHINGTON -- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) announced
Tuesday that its management has decided to propose to the
executive board to resume financial assistance for Ukraine as the
government has made progress in the fiscal and structural areas.
</P>
<P>
A board meeting will be scheduled before the end of March to
consider this issue, the IMF said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The IMF approved last September a three-year extended
arrangement for Ukraine, equivalent to 2.25 billion U.S. dollars,
to support the government's 1998-2001 economic program. Of the
total, 300 million dollars has already been disbursed. (IMF-
Ukraine)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The World Bank approved Tuesday a loan of 71
million U.S. dollars for China's container transport project,
which will facilitate the inland movement of seaborne containers
from gateway ports to inland cities.
</P>
<P>
This project will help alleviate infrastructure bottlenecks in
China by developing an inland distribution system for seaborne
containers and improving service quality of the container inland
distribution market, the bank said in a statement. (WB-China)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico is expected to attract a capital inflow
of 10.1 billion U.S. dollars in 1999, up 8 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
 Mexican Commerce Secretary Herminio Blanco said investment by
foreign companies, including Volkswagen, will create 41,500 jobs.
</P>
<P>
The foreign companies' investment plans were unveiled on
Tuesday at a meeting in Los Pinos Presidential Palace, in the
presence of President Ernesto Zedillo. (Mexico-Foreign Investment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italy's target of cutting budget deficit to 2 percent
of gross domestic product (GDP) by the end of this year is
feasible, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) said Tuesday at
the end of an annual mission here.
</P>
<P>
The IMF team, which started an inspection on Italy's poor
economic conditions on March 3, said in its report that the
country's economic growth would be between 1 and 2 percent this
year, below the European Union (EU) average.
</P>
<P>
Italy has made great strides in entering the euro zone but
more structural reforms are needed if it is to maintain
competitiveness with its partners, the IMF added.( IMF-Italy
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- A new agreement between producers to rescue
depressed oil prices will help Venezuela avoid shutting down a
third of the country's oil wells, Venezuela's Energy and Mines
Minister Ali Rodriguez said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela, Iran, Algeria, Saudi Arabia and Mexico agreed on
March 12 to cut oil production to less than 2 million barrels a
day (Bpd) as of April. Norway, Oman and Russia joined the
agreement this week. (Venezuela-Oil cuts) 
</P>
