<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Currency Depreciates Sharply Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Romania's national currency,
the leu, plummeted to 14,040 against the U.S. dollar on Monday,
losing 356 units compared with the previous trading day.
</P>
<P>
It is the biggest devaluation of the leu since the beginning of
this year.
</P>
<P>
The foreign exchange market opened 14,020 lei against the U.S.
dollar and closed 14,600 lei per dollar, with an average rate of
exchange calculated by Romania's central bank of 14,040 lei for
one U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Due to lack of confidence in the leu, traders stopped selling
dollars and plunged into buying dollars and other hard currencies.
Some bourses had to suspend trading dollars since their reserves
have been exhausted.
</P>
<P>
The leu has depreciated steadily since the start of the year.
It was kept stable briefly last week after the government took
measures such as raising interest rates to curb its downward trend.
</P>
<P>
However, the leu began to lose its value again this week and
dropped to below 14,000 lei against the dollar on Monday, which
roused concerns that the country may have lost control over its
national currency.
</P>
<P>
Experts contribute the sharp devaluation to a continued
economic recession, the banking crisis and the soaring fuel prices
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The financial authorities may further raise interest rates and
issue high-yield state bonds to prop up the leu, experts predict.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Government Approves New Citizenship Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 16 (Xinhua) -- After weeks of debate, the German
government has approved the draft of a new citizenship law that
will give limited dual nationality to children born to foreign
residents.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the law is to facilitate the integration of
foreign residents into the German nation, the government said.
</P>
<P>
In a historic change to the nation's 1913 citizenship law, the
draft stipulates that children born to foreign residents would
automatically receive German citizenship. They would also be able
to keep their parents' nationality, but would have to choose one
or the other by the age of 23.
</P>
<P>
Due to strong resistance from opposition parties and many
German residents, the government, which had planned to make
unlimited dual nationality the rule, decided to reconsider and
amend some of the related issues.
</P>
<P>
Another major amendment and vital consideration to the current
law is shortening the duration of stay for foreigners applying for
German citizenship.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft bill, which was passed at a special cabinet
meeting, foreigners who want German citizenship need to reside in
Germany for eight years, seven years shorter than the previous
limit.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Otto Schily said a reform of the present
citizenship law is intended to promote the integration of foreign
residents and Germans, and to make it clear that "Germany is an
open and modernized country."
</P>
<P>
He also said that those who want to be German citizens should
not only understand Germany's constitution and meet some minimum
requirements, but also master the German language as stipulated in
the new law.
</P>
<P>
The bill will take effect on January 1, 2000, after being
ratified by both houses of the parliament and accepted by a
majority of the people.
</P>
<P>
Germany has nearly 7.4 million foreign residents, nearly 10
percent of the population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
