<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Fishing Boats Allowed in Maldivian Waters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Maldivian government has
permitted Sri Lankan boats to pass through Maldivian territorial
waters to reach international seas for fishing, reports reaching
here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This follows talks recently between the governments of the two
countries to help Sri Lankan fishermen who face difficulties in
venturing out to international waters for fishing, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement signed after the talks, Sri Lankan
fishermen must inform the Maldivian authorities 18 hours in
advance.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the fishermen's information should also
include the name of the captain and the boat, its size, the
registered harbor and the registration number, as well as the
speed and direction of the boat.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the Maldivian authorities have detained more
than 50 Sri Lankan boats in the Maldivian waters, of which 15 have
already been confiscated.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government has spent more than 100,000 U.S.
dollars for the release of these fishermen, their vessels and
fishing gear. 
</P>
</TEXT>
