<HEADLINE> WBC Claims Lewis Robbed of "Clear Victory" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The World Boxing Council (WBC)
claimed in a statement issued here on Tuesday that its heavyweight
champion Lennox Lewis was robbed of his "clear victory" against
World Boxing Association (WBA) rival Evander Holyfield in their
unification battle.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Lewis was thought by many as having outclassed
American Evander Holyfield in the 12 rounds bout in New York
Saturday. But none of the boxers won the undisputed world
heavyweight boxing title when judges scored the fight a draw with
a decision that triggered a wide-spreading controversy.
</P>
<P>
"Lewis was unjustly robbed of a clear victory," the WBC
statement said, calling for a rematch with "clearer rules." It
said that Lewis "massacred Holyfield with an endless number of
devastating blows."
</P>
<P>
The WBC joined widespread criticism of WBA-appointed Eugenia
Williams, the only judge at the fight who awarded Holyfield the
victory.
</P>
<P>
"Our explanation is the little experience Ms Williams has for a
fight of this level and an excessive favoritism for a boxer of her
own country."
</P>
<P>
Williams was reportedly to have complained she had a poor view
and mainly saw Lewis' back during the fifth round in which Lewis
was believed to have landed 43 punches to 11 for Holyfield. The
woman judge had defended her score, saying that she had acted
according to what she saw during the fight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
