<HEADLINE> Honduran Soldiers Join Police to End Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Some 12,000 Honduran Army
soldiers joined the police Tuesday to end the wave of violence
that is sweeping through this Central American country.
</P>
<P>
The move followed the order by President Carlos Flores to
deploy troops along the streets throughout the country,
particularly in densely populated areas.
</P>
<P>
The president has instructed Security Minister Elizabeth Chiuz
Sierra and Defense Minister Edgardo Dumas Rodriguez to coordinate
a joint operation between the military and police.
</P>
<P>
In the urban areas, soldiers were observed moving to areas
frequented by armed gangs of youths who often cast a shadow of
fear over the resident population.
</P>
<P>
At least five kidnappings have been reported so far this year.
In one case, parents had to pay a ransom to retrieve their seven-
year-old son.
</P>
<P>
While affected by violence ranging from kidnappings to armed
bank robberies, Honduras has also remained in a state of emergency
since hurricane "Mitch" devastated the country near the end of
last year.
</P>
<P>
Almost 6,000 people were reported dead and 8,000 missing during
the disaster, which left another 12,000 injured and 1.5 million
homeless.
</P>
<P>
Honduras has also seen a daily rationing of power since
February as a result of a fire in one of the transformers of the
country's principal hydro-electric plant. The plant has the
capacity to produce 300 megawatts of electricity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
