<HEADLINE> Continued Dialogues Across Straits Desired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Political dialogues across the
Taiwan Straits should continue, suggests a mainland official.
</P>
<P>
"We hope during Wang Daohan's visit to Taiwan, the two sides
will continue political dialogues and deal with deeper issues,"
Tang Shubei, secretary-general of Beijing-based Association for
Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (Arats), was quoted as saying
by today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
"Not only should we continue exchanging our views freely, but
we should go one step further on the basis of last year's meeting,
" he added when meeting the press yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Wang, Arats' chairman, met Koo Chen-fu, chairman of Taipei-
based Straits Exchange Foundation (Sef), in Shanghai last October.
Wang and Koo candidly discussed a wide range of issues. The
meeting marked a resumption of high-level contacts across the
Straits. Contacts were suspended in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The two reached a consensus in October regarding Wang's visit,
which they said would take place at an appropriate time, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
Arats proposed this year's visit, he added.
</P>
<P>
Tang refuted Sef's allegation Arats has been dilatory in
preparing for Wang's visit.
</P>
<P>
To date, Arats and Sef have not contacted each other regarding
Wang's visit, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
It is unlikely, however, Wang will be able to visit Taiwan
before May, due to his tight schedule, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
Arats deputy secretary-general Li Yafei is scheduled to arrive
in Taipei today to finalize details of Wang's visit.
</P>
<P>
Tang, calling Wang's visit a continuation of Koo's visit, hopes
Wang will visit Taiwan under the atmosphere of progress.
</P>
<P>
"Of course, this is not determined solely by our side but by
joint efforts," Tang said.
</P>
<P>
The associations should sort out some issues and decide if they
can reach a consensus, Tang suggested.
</P>
<P>
Among the issues Tang mentioned were the "one China" matter,
opposition to Taiwan's independence, hostilities across the
Straits and enhancement of economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We share quite a few things in common," Tang said, "If we
truly observe the principle of seeking common ground while
respecting difference, it will be possible for us to find more in
common within many issues, to solve issues gradually and further
our political dialogues," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
