<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Recovery to Take Several Years: ABARE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Asia's economic recovery would
take several years, Australia's chief official commodities
forecaster the Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource
Economics (ABARE) warned here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
ABARE said world growth is set to further weaken in 1999, with
instability worsening in Russia and Latin America while Asia
struggles to recover.
</P>
<P>
ABARE's March commodity outlook said it holds concerns for
Japan through to 2004.
</P>
<P>
"The situation remains difficult elsewhere in East Asia and
Southeast Asia, especially in Indonesia and Malaysia," it said.
</P>
<P>
"The economic recovery in the Asian region is likely to take
several years."
</P>
<P>
It said agricultural commodity prices dipped by up to 30
percent in 1998, and a crucial issue for commodity producers was
how long commodity prices would remain low.
</P>
<P>
"Economic commentators are increasingly of the belief that
world commodity prices are likely to remain relatively low for
some time," ABARE said.
</P>
<P>
"A major factor underlying this price assessment is an assumed
weak world economic outlook.
</P>
<P>
"Thus commodity demand is not expected to recover
significantly, at least not in the short term," it said.
</P>
<P>
ABARE said world economic growth would slow to 1.9 percent in
1999 from 2.3 percent in 1998, before a modest recovery in 2000
takes it to 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Beyond 2000, world economic growth is seen strengthening to up
to 3.3 percent a year over the medium term.
</P>
<P>
ABARE also warned that an oversupply of commodities could
undermine a price recovery.
</P>
<P>
Its outlook also predicted:
</P>
<P>
-- Japanese economic growth to remain sluggish;
</P>
<P>
-- China's growth to moderate;
</P>
<P>
-- Economic growth of the Organization for Economic Cooperation
and Development (OECD) to decline to 1.8 percent in 1999 from 2.1
percent in 1998, recovering to 2 percent in 2000 and then climbing
to 2.3 percent beyond 2000;
</P>
<P>
-- Growth of the United States to moderate to 2.7 percent in
1999 from 3.9 percent in 1998 and strengthen to 2.4 percent in
2000.
</P>
<P>
-- West European growth to decline to 1.9 percent in 1999
before climbing to 2.2 percent in 2000 and then sustained at 2.4
percent;
</P>
<P>
-- Non-OECD Asian growth (excluding Japan and South Korea) to
increase marginally;
</P>
<P>
-- Latin America to come under significant pressures in early
1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
