<HEADLINE> Hotline Offers Help to Laid-Off Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A tip-off hotline went into
operation yesterday at the Ministry of Labor and Social Security
to help guard against infringement of the rights of redundant
workers.
</P>
<P>
The hotline was designed to enable the Ministry to have quicker
and better access to information about any violations against the
rights of redundant workers, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Laid-off workers are encouraged to come up with the hotline if
they do not benefit from state preferential policies in job
hunting.
</P>
<P>
Hotline officials would deal with problems in managing re-
employment funds and malpractice in re-employment centers.
</P>
<P>
Enterprise-based re-employment centers are responsible for 6.09
million workers laid off from state-owned enterprises, according
to latest statistics.
</P>
<P>
Once registered at a re-employment center, a redundant worker
would receive a government subsidy and retain their insurance
rights. Such centers are also obliged to provide job-oriented
training and information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
