<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Establish Erosion-Monitoring System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- China plans to establish a
national water and soil erosion-control monitoring system this
year, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest report from the Ministry of Water
Resources, the proposed network, the first of its kind in China,
includes a monitoring system and an information transmitting and
data-processing system.
</P>
<P>
The network is projected to be completed in stages and be
operational before 2010, and will cost an estimated 866 million
yuan (104 million US dollars), the paper quoted a ministry
official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The network will be built at five levels, including a Beijing-
based State erosion-control monitoring center, several monitoring
hubs built along China's seven longest rivers and lakes, 30
provincial stations, 2,015 data-collecting sites and 155
monitoring branches in specially designed zones.
</P>
<P>
These zones will be capable of controlling 5.72 million square
km of erosion-prone land, and as a result about 59 percent of
China's territory could be monitored, according to the official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0308 </DOCNO>
