<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Economy Predicted to Bottom Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government Tuesday
predicted that the country's crisis-hit economy should bottom out
in the first semester of the 1999/2000 fiscal year beginning in
April after shrinking by an estimated 16 percent in the current
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The inflation, running at an estimated 66 percent in the
current fiscal year, should moderate to within a range of 15 to 20
percent in 1999/2000, the government said in its supplementary
memorandum of economic and financial policies, a new letter of
intent to the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
"Our central projection is for the real gross domestic product
(GDP) in 1999/2000 to be virtually unchanged, based on the
expectation that the economy will bottom out during the first half
of the fiscal year and that a modest recovery will begin
thereafter," The Jakarta Post Wednesday quoted the letter as
saying.
</P>
<P>
But it warned that a number of domestic and external risks
apply to the outlook, and the macroeconomic framework would be
reviewed regularly to ensure that policies remain consistent.
</P>
<P>
The government said it remains committed to pursuing a tight
monetary policy to stabilize prices and reduce the volatility of
the rupiah.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit for 1999/2000 is projected to be 6 percent
of the GDP, with the assumption that the rupiah averages at 7,500
rupiah per U.S. dollar and the government collects 1.5 billion
dollars from its privatization program.
</P>
<P>
The government hopes to get an additional official external
support of about 5 billion dollars to plug the budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
On international trade, the government believes Indonesia's
balance of payments in 1999/2000 should improve steadily, with
export growth contributing to a "somewhat larger" external trade
surplus.
</P>
<P>
With that surplus, coupled with incoming official funds, the
country's gross external reserves are expected to increase to a
"more comfortable level" of around 29 billion dollars, compared
with the 24-billion-dollar level now.
</P>
<P>
To restore foreign investor confidence in the country, the
government said it would continue with its bank restructuring
measures and help solve private external debt hangover and improve
the legal structure.
</P>
<P>
The government decided on Saturday to close down 38 domestic
private banks, nationalize seven, recapitalize nine and let 73
relatively healthy ones continue operations.
</P>
<P>
It promised to complete the recapitalization process for the
nine banks by June 30.
</P>
<P>
To help solve the debt hangover, the government expects an
agreement with external private creditors to be reached on a
second interbank exchange offer to cover debts falling due during
the 1999/2000 period.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the IMF will disburse 1 billion dollars if
its board of directors approves the letter of intent.
</P>
<P>
The IMF is organizing a 43-billion-U.S.-dollar bailout for
Indonesia. The fund has already disbursed some 9 billion dollars
from its own commitment of 11.3 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
