<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serbs Protest Rulings by International Overseers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of thousands of Bosnian
Serbs held rallies on Tuesday, protesting against the
international officials' decision to fire Nikola Poplasen as
Bosnian Serb President and to end unilateral Serb control over the
key city of Brcko.
</P>
<P>
The protesters, rallying in the cities of Banija Luka, Pale,
Bileca, Bratunac and Srebrenica, decried the International High
Representative Carlos Wenstendorp and American arbitrator Roberts
Owen as breaching the Dayton peace accord and urged them to back
down on their decisions.
</P>
<P>
President of the Bosnian Presidency Zivko Radisic, Poplasen and
Speaker of the National Assembly of the Republic of Srpska joined
the demonstrations, the Tanjug news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The National Assembly of the Republic of Srpska passed a
resolution on March 7, rejecting the two international overseers'
rulings two days earlier as violating the Dayton peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The following day, Wenstendorp refused to accept the Serb
parliament's rejection to his decision to sack Poplasen. He also
appealed to Serb representatives to accept Owen's decision on
setting up a neutral district in Brcko and putting it under joint
Serb, Croat and Muslim administration.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.S. brokered Dayton peace agreement that ended the
1992-1995 Bosnian war, Brcko, a city with a population of 90,000
and a key port on the Sava river, is a Serb entity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
