<HEADLINE> Colombian Army Denies 70 Deaths in Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian Army
denied Tuesday that 73 people had been killed in fighting in the
last few days between paramilitary groups and rebels in a village
in Bolivar province.
</P>
<P>
The claims from the Defense Council on the numbers of fallen
were false, said General Raphael Hernandez Lopez, Chief of the
Colombian Army, who visited the troubled village.
</P>
<P>
So far this year there have been 69 deaths and 3,619 people
displaced due to the fighting between the two sides in the Los
Montes de Maria village in Bolivar province.
</P>
<P>
The defense council in the village said that 2,021 of the
displaced peoples are children, 803 are women and 795 men.
</P>
<P>
The village has asked the Ministry of Defense and Interior to
intervene and put an end to the violence immediately.
</P>
<P>
The governor of Bolivar province, Miguel Read, confirmed that
units of the military had tried to penetrate the region to retake
control.
</P>
<P>
The conflict in Colombia has claimed more than 35,000 lives in
just a decade. The financial cost of the war is running at about
four billion dollars a year, or four percent of its gross domestic
product, according to government estimates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
