<HEADLINE> Hungary Concerned Over EU Commissioners' Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Hungary said Tuesday that it is
concerned at the resignation of the entire European Union (EU)
Commission and hoped it would not affect the EU's internal reform
and eastward enlargement.
</P>
<P>
The government of Hungary will study the situation of the EU
after the organization's powerful commission resigned, Foreign
Ministry spokesman Horvath Gabor was quoted by the Hungarian
Telegraph Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Horvath is confident that the EU's work, such as the internal
reform, the agenda of the year 2000 and the negotiations on
candidate countries to join the EU, will be transferred to the
European Parliament and the rotating EU presidency state.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that, according to the agenda, Hungary
will continue its ministerial talks with Germany this June on
joining the EU which holds the bloc's presidency.
</P>
<P>
Hungary's preparation to enter the EU and its agenda will not
be affected by the resignations, Horvath said.
</P>
<P>
The 20 EU commissioners resigned en masse early on Tuesday
morning after a panel of five independent experts appointed by the
European Parliament published a report, accusing them of losing
control over fraud, nepotism and financial mismanagement in their
departments.
</P>
<P>
The resignation came just nine days before an EU summit is due
to open in Berlin to discuss the future of the organization's
financing and the reform of its major policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
