<HEADLINE> Austria Welcomes Resignation of EU Commissioners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Federal Chancellor Viktor
Klima said here Tuesday that the 20 commissioners of the European
Union (EU) had made the right decision in resigning en masse.
</P>
<P>
The resignation of the whole EU powerful executive was "a step
to maintain cleanness and transparency". The EU now had to take
measures to restore the trust in it, Klima said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Vice Chancellor and Foreign Minister Wolfgang
Schuessel said, "The current crisis (of the EU) is a chance to
have a new start".
</P>
<P>
All the commissioners announced Tuesday morning their decision
to resign after a panel of five independent experts appointed by
the European Parliament published a report, accusing the 20 of
losing control over fraud, nepotism and financial mismanagement in
their departments.
</P>
<P>
The collapse of the commission leaves the EU's 15 member states
facing an institutional crisis just nine days before a summit in
Berlin at which they are due to negotiate on the future of the
bloc's financing and the reform of its major policies. 
</P>
