<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shandong's Coastal Waters Contaminated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Water in inland areas near the
coast of east China's Shandong Province is seriously contaminated,
partly because of the drainage of industrial wastes and domestic
sewage.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey shows that the quality of the water in this
region is acceptable so long as it is about 3,000 meters from the
local coast, but the water closer to the coast is much more highly
polluted.
</P>
<P>
Bays and estuaries where polluted water flows into sea are the
most seriously contaminated.
</P>
<P>
Among the pollutants dumped into this water are mainly from
fertilizers used in agriculture and aqua-culture.
</P>
<P>
Soil erosion and the increasing use of washing detergent are
also among the leading contaminators of the sea waters.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that during the 1989-1997 period, as many as 35
red tides occurred in local inshore sea areas, resulting in more
than one billion yuan in economic losses for the local fishing
industry.
</P>
<P>
Shandong Province has 3,100 kilometers of coastline, fully one-
sixth of China's total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
