<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angry Former Olympians Challenge IOC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Disillusioned over the bribery
scandal of the International Olympic Committee (IOC), a group of
Canadian former Olympians launched on Tuesday in Lausanne an
athletes' coalition to challenge the world governing body of
Olympic sports.
</P>
<P>
Led by 1992 Olympic champion swimmer Mark Tewksbury, OATH (
Olympic Advocates Together Honorably) hopes to help restore the
tarnished Olympic spirit and act as a watchdog over the IOC. IOC
will meet this week in Lausanne to clean house after the biggest
and most damaging bribery scandal in its history.
</P>
<P>
"I have watched with great sadness in the past three months as
the spirit of the Olympics has been betrayed by the actions of the
IOC," Tewksbury, one of the founders of the new council, was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want to attack any one individual in the IOC but the
system itself. I no longer believe in it (the IOC). I don't
believe in its leadership," he said.
</P>
<P>
Angered by the corruption scandal, Tewksbury resigned last
month from his posts in the Canadian Olympic Association, the
International Amateur Swimming Federation (FINA) and the Toronto
2008 Olympic bid committee.
</P>
<P>
The group also includes two-time Olympic silver medalist
speedskater Susan Auch, paralympian marathon medalist Andre Viger,
former Olympian rower Heather Clarke and athlete advocate Ann Peel.
</P>
<P>
"It's time for the IOC to change," said OATH co-founder and
Magna vice-president Keith Stein. "It is now time for democracy,
not aristocracy," he said.
</P>
<P>
With own source of funding, OATH wishes to remain independent
from the Olympic movement and, to avoid any possible IOC
interference, it kept itself secret until Tuesday. "We're up
against a pretty big force -- the IOC. We didn't want anything to
undermine this. We wanted to ensure we could get out of the gate,
" said Tewksbury.
</P>
<P>
"We received information of this initiative, which was
apparently secret until now," IOC director general Francois
Carrard said IOC had received information of the group but didn't
understand why it was kept secret. "But we'll certainly give a
look at the project," he said.
</P>
<P>
Spearheaded by Canadians though, OATH hopes to rally athletes
from around the world. And an international symposium has been
planned to be held in June.
</P>
<P>
The group said several other athletes, including American
Olympic champion speedskater Dan Jansen had shown strong interests
on the group. 
</P>
