<HEADLINE> U.S. to Continue Low-Level Flight in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. EA-6B jets would
continue the low-level flight in Italy despite last year's cable
car disaster that killed 20 lives, the head of a U.S. military
team checking new flight safety measures in Italy said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I think, not only for our country and for the Italians but for
the NATO nations, that low-level flying proficiency is something
we need to maintain," Navy Admiral Joseph Prueher said.
</P>
<P>
Prueher was assigned by Defense Secretary William Cohen to go
to Italy and work closely with the Italian military on new safety
measures after last year's accident in which the U.S. Marine Corps
EA-6B jet severed a cable car cable, sending the cable car
plunging to the ground and killing 20 skiers on it.
</P>
<P>
The pilot of the plane was acquitted of manslaughter and other
serious charges in a military trial in North Carolina this month.
And similar charges were also dropped against the plane's
navigator on Monday.
</P>
<P>
But both men still face trial on obstruction of justice charges.
</P>
<P>
Prueher and Italian Air Force Lt. Gen. Leonardo Tricarico head
a joint team which will look into new safety measures set up for
aircraft at Aviano Air Base, where the EA-6B was based, and at
other military airfields and to see if further measures are needed.
</P>
</TEXT>
