<HEADLINE> New Crops Expected to Raise China's Grain Yield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- High-yield crops are expected to
boost China's grain output by 4 million tons this year, according
to the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
A ministry official told China Daily that the country will
promote the use of 50 top-quality high-yielding strains of paddy
rice, wheat and corn in more than 6.6 million hectares of farm
land.
</P>
<P>
"The application of Agro-technical skills and service this
year will focus on optimizing the crop-growing structure,
developing high-efficiency agriculture and increasing farmers'
income," said Xu Weisheng, chief of the ministry's National Agro-
Technical Enhancement and service Center (NATESC).
</P>
<P>
"We will set aside an additional 333,300 hectares of crop land
for high-quality early indica rice in the nine provinces of
southern China, increasing the total area for quality early rice
in the region to about 2.7 million hectares," Today's China Daily
quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The plan is expected to increase the region's grain yield by
about 1 million tons, and add 2 billion yuan to local revenues, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the center promoted the planting of 24 high-quality
rice strains and the use of accessory technologies in southern
China, increasing per hectare production by 489 kilograms,
indicate NATESC statistics.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, about 58.3 percent of the acreage for paddy rice,
wheat and corn was planted with improved varieties, according to
Xu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
