<HEADLINE> Menem Accepts Opposition Challenges on Referendum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President Carlos
Menem on Tuesday accepted opposition challenges to call a national
referendum on whether he can run for a third term in the October
general election.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the headquarters of the Mechanics Union in the
capital city, the president said he would hold a plebiscite if its
outcome was legally binding and would override a constitutional
ban on presidents serving three consecutive terms.
</P>
<P>
The request to hold a referendum, raised last week by the
opposing alliance, was intended to stop the possibility that Menem
would run for a third consecutive term as the country's chief
leader.
</P>
<P>
The 68-year-old president was elected in 1989 and re-elected in
1995, after striking a deal with the opposition to change the
constitution to allow him to run for a second term.
</P>
<P>
The constitution now forbids three consecutive terms. Menem has
not yet said publicly that he wants to run for the presidency for
the third time in October. 
</P>
