<HEADLINE> Northeast Chinese Industrial City's Foreign Trade Surges in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Shenyang, capital of northeast
China's Liaoning Province, scored an increase of 45 percent in its
import and export volume in the first month of this year.
</P>
<P>
Information from Shenyang Customs Office said the city's
foreign trade volume in January stood at 120 million U.S. dollars,
up 45 percent according to comparable figure of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Breaking down the figures, imports were 73.73 million U.S.
dollars, up 60 percent, while exports were 46.37 million U.S.
dollars, a rise of 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
A local foreign trade official said Shenyang had negative
growth in foreign trade in a period last year due to the adverse
impact of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
But the city adjusted commodity structure for foreign trade,
while making efforts to export new foreign trade markets in
regions including West Europe, which has proved effective, said
the official.
</P>
<P>
China faces great difficulties in its foreign trade and
economic cooperation in the new year, but Chinese foreign trade
Minister Shi Guangsheng pledged that China would make great
efforts to increase foreign trade and achieve a balance between
imports and exports in 1999 following a 15-year-low decrease in
trade volume in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Hit by the Asian financial crisis, China's foreign trade
dropped 0.4 percent in 1998 to reach 323.93 billion US dollars,
the first year of negative growth since 1983.  
</P>
</TEXT>
