<HEADLINE> Street Galleries Popular in East China's City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese customer who bought a
replica of Vincent Van Gogh's painting "Sunflowers" at a local
gallery says he's happy with it because he can enjoy art at a
relatively small cost.
</P>
<P>
There are many of these customers at the city's galleries,
which have grown with the demand. There are about 200 of them in
Qingdao, in Shandong Province, mostly selling Chinese water colors
and a few prints and oil paintings.
</P>
<P>
Many of their owners are painters who are known around Shandong.
One says that most of his patrons were intellectuals in the past
but that now his customers represent a broader spectrum of city
life.
</P>
<P>
Their purchases seem to be mostly for decorating apartments or
houses. There are very few buyers who are serious collectors.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao people prefer traditional Chinese paintings, says Xu
Xiuwu, the vice-president of the Arts Association of Qingdao, and
framed pictures are gaining in popularity while scrolls are
declining.
</P>
<P>
However, Xu says, galleries operate on a rather low level and
need to embrace the artist, agent, and critic all together and to
make a greater effort to increase artistic awareness in customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
