<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Italy's 1999 Budget Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Italy's target of cutting budget
deficit to 2 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) by the end of
this year is feasible, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) said
Tuesday at the end of an annual mission here.
</P>
<P>
The IMF team, which started an inspection on Italy's poor
economic conditions on March 3, said in its report that the
country's economic growth would be between 1 and 2 percent this
year, below the European Union (EU) average.
</P>
<P>
Italy has made great strides in entering the euro zone but more
structural reforms are needed if it is to maintain competitiveness
with its partners, the IMF added.
</P>
<P>
The IMF also backed Italy's goal of reducing budget deficit to
1 percent of GDP by 2001 and balancing the budget the year after.
But it stressed that "this can only be seen as a minimal goal."
</P>
<P>
The report praised measures taken to liberalize the labor
market, reiterated its criticism of a proposed 35-hour working
week, and called for further moves to deregulate the economy.
</P>
<P>
In a formal reply to the report, the Italian Ministry of
Treasury issued a statement Tuesday evening, saying it "accepts
the invitation to consolidate the work of deficit-cutting and to
complete the reform of the Italian economy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
