<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0345 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-Public Sector in Shaanxi Grows Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Shaanxi Province
ranks first in the country in the growth of the non-public sector
over the past year.
</P>
<P>
To date, individually-owned businesses in the province number
765,000, up 22.7 percent from the figure a year ago, and the
number of private firms surged 40.7 percent to 34,000.
</P>
<P>
The output value generated by the non-public sector in its
gross domestic product has risen from 11.8 percent to 18 percent,
said Jia Zhibang, vice governor of Shaanxi.
</P>
<P>
Some 10 percent of the province's revenue came from the non-
public sector last year, with the figure standing at 40 percent in
some counties.
</P>
<P>
Individual or self-employed firms provide 95 percent of the non-
staple food to the residents of medium and large cities in Shaanxi.
</P>
<P>
Jia named rapid growth and the rational development of industry
as the major characteristics of the non-public sector.
</P>
<P>
The number of newly registered non-public firms in 1998 was 44
percent of all such firms existing there in the previous 20 years,
and their combined registered capital was 73 percent of the total
amount for the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Jia attributes the rapid growth of the non-public sector to
simplified registration procedures, preferential treatment in
taxation and loans, and curbs on the arbitrary collection of fines
and fees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
