<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0346 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Hails Oil Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A new agreement between producers
to rescue depressed oil prices will help Venezuela avoid shutting
down a third of the country's oil wells, Venezuela's Energy and
Mines Minister Ali Rodriguez said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela, Iran, Algeria, Saudi Arabia and Mexico agreed on
March 12 to cut oil production to less than 2 million barrels a
day (Bpd) as of April. Norway, Oman and Russia joined the
agreement this week.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez said at a press conference that if there had been no
agreement on an additional cut, oil prices would have fallen to
below 6 U.S. dollars a barrel, which would have obligated the
Venezuelan Petroleum company to close a third of the oil wells
because of the high cost of production.
</P>
<P>
The oil producing countries have agreed on a global oil
production cut of five million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez said that because of production reductions, the price
of Brent crude may reach 18 dollars a barrel by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
In two days the Venezuelan basket has risen 39 cents to 10.30
dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan export basket, which is made up of crude and
refined products, fell to a minimum of 7.76 dollars per barrel
last month and, according to Rodriguez, could have fallen below 7
dollars this quarter.
</P>
<P>
Though Rodriguez declined to reveal the total amount of the
Venezuelan cut under the agreement, delegates from the
Organization of Oil Producing Countries told the local press that
the South American country would reduce production by 125,000
barrels daily. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
