<HEADLINE> Hoddle: I Still Pinch Myself About England Sacking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Former England mananger Glenn
Hoddle still has to pinch himself six weeks after being sacked
from the office.
</P>
<P>
The 40-year-old former national boss was relieved of his duties
last month following his reported comments on the disabled and
reincarnation.
</P>
<P>
"I pinch myself sometimes and think I should still be going
into the office and should still be preparing for the France game,
" said Hoddle.
</P>
<P>
"Every now and again it hits you. If we'd lost three games on
the trot and I got the sack...c'est la vie, that's life and that's
the football life.
</P>
<P>
"But it's not and that's what is so sad about the case," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Hoddle still feels his comments, reported in an interview with
The Times newspaper, were misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
"I must get people to understand that what I actually ended up
getting the sack about, the punishment for disabled people from
other lifetimes - it's not my belief and it's not what I said.
</P>
<P>
"I think we have the choice to come back into whatever
circumstances in the next lifetime. I would never dream of saying
that there's a punishment bestowed upon people who are disabled,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Hoddle also defended his World Cup diary, co-written with the
Football Association's acting executive director David Davies,
which was seen by his critics as a factor in his eventual
departure.
</P>
<P>
"If it was the most boring book ever written, about how we ate
eggs for breakfast and had coffee before we went to bed, they
would still have ripped it apart, but you don't let those sort of
people dictate your life," he added. 
</P>
