<HEADLINE> Greenspan Says No Different Monetary Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan said Tuesday that it has no different monetary
policies for different Fed Districts as was the case in the very
early years.
</P>
<P>
In today's integrated national markets, he said, "monetary
policy decisions, of course, must be directed toward what is
deemed to be the best path for the economy as a whole".
</P>
<P>
Greenspan devoted a speech mainly on U.S. farming in San
Francisco to what he called "one of the more notable soft spots"
in a U.S. economy he termed both impressive and robust.
</P>
<P>
"We at the Federal Reserve are often asked by representatives
of troubled sectors of the economy whether their voices truly are
heard in our policy proceedings", he said, "I can assure you that
they are, most notably in the reports on regional economic
conditions that are a regular part of the preparations for the
meetings of the Federal Open Market Committee and in reports from
Reserve Bank presidents that are a regular part of the policy
discussions themselves."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Fed's responsibility on monitoring the
safety and soundness of the banking system required them to seek
better understanding of the regional and sectoral composition of
changes in prices and activity and of their effects on finance.
</P>
<P>
"Among other things", he added,"We have devoted special
attention over the years to the collection and interpretation of
data from community banks that are heavily involved in
agricultural lending, a sector of the economy in which these
smaller banks still appear to have a strong comparative
advantage."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
