<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0352 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Adopts New System of Classifying Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government has
introduced a new business classification system which recognizes
such features of modern life as the fact that computers run on
electricity, government officials said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The North American Industry Classification System, replacing
the six-decade-old Standard Industry Classification system, will
allow the government to separately track such new businesses as
fiber-optic cable manufacturing, cellular telephone service, and
telemarketing.
</P>
<P>
Previously, service-industry data on haircuts and brain surgery
were all dropped in the same statistical pot while computers were
counted in nonelectrical machinery because the first computers
were likened to adding machines, and adding machines are
hand-cranked, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The new system provides 1,170 industry classifications, 15
percent more than the old system. It includes 358 new industries,
390 revised classifications and 422 industries that will be
measured the same way as before.
</P>
<P>
Users of government statistics received their first glimpse of
the new system on Tuesday in the Census Bureau's advance report on
the 1997 Economic Census. It revealed, for instance, that the
information sector -- movies, broadcasting, telecommunications,
data-processing -- provided 3.2 million jobs at 115,000 locations
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The new system was jointly developed with Canada and Mexico and
will make comparisons among the signatories of the North American
Free Trade Agreement easier, the officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
