<HEADLINE> World Bank Announces Debarment of Canadian Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- In its effort to eliminate
fraud and corruption, the World Bank declared on Tuesday that
Canadax Technologies Inc., a Canadian firm, and its president,
Pierre Savignac, permanently ineligible to be awarded any
contracts financed by the bank.
</P>
<P>
The sanction was imposed after the bank concluded that Canadax
engaged in fraudulent conduct during the procurement of a World
Bank-financed contract in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
"When contractors fail to observe the highest of ethical
standards during the bidding process, as happened in this
instance, we will debar bidders, suppliers, contractors or
consultants from bidding an Bank-financed contracts. In this case,
we concluded that permanent debarment was clearly warranted," said
James D. Wolfensohn, president of the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The bank's Sanctions Committee found that the Canadax case
involved the forgery of two letters of credit. Canadax submitted
the letters as bid and performance securities in the context of
the bidding for, and the award of, a World Bank-financed contract
for the supply of computers to the Ministry of Culture and
Education in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
The committee agreed on the recommendation against Canadax after
reviewing a report prepared by the bank's Internal Auditing
Department and a response submitted by the accused firm in which
Savignac denied any direct responsibility for the forgeries.
</P>
<P>
Since the Sanctions Committee was set up in November 1998, four
cases have been submitted for review. the present case is the
first to result in a recommendation to the president of the
bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
