<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
on Tuesday voiced its satisfaction with the unfolding peace
process over Papua New Guinea's secession-troubled island of
Bougainville.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press here, the president of the
15-member of the Security Council, Qin Huasun of China, said,
"Members of the Council express their satisfaction with the smooth
development of the peace process and the upholding of the ceasefire
by the parties concerned."
</P>
<P>
The statement came after the Security Council was briefed by
the U.N. Secretariat on the latest development of the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Council members also expressed their hope the parties would
continue their efforts to establish a reconciliation government in
Bougainville in accordance with an agreement signed in 1998, said
Qin, who is Chinese permanent representative to the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
The 15 Council members also hoped that the disarmament process
could be accelerated, he said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed at Lincoln University, New Zealand,
sought to end a 10-year secessionist rebellion in which up to
20,000 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
An election is to be held on Bougainville next month. Voters
will choose representatives who will negotiate with the Papua New
Guinea government until a reconciliation government is established
on Bougainville later in the year. 
</P>
