<HEADLINE> Schroeder, Blair Trying to Hunt for New EU Boss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- British and German leaders on
Tuesday agreed that the European Union will try to name a new
president for the European Commission at next week's Berlin
Summit.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair and Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder made
the announcement at Blair's Downing Street residence in London
after holding talks.
</P>
<P>
"We recognize that the situation has changed dramatically and
we have to act," Blair told a joint news conference.
</P>
<P>
"We have obviously had a long and detailed discussion about the
committee. We agreed there are certain actions it is necessary to
take as swiftly as possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the British leader told parliament before meeting
Schroeder that Santer should leave his caretaker post as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
"We have to find a new Commission president quickly, without
putting ourselves under unnecessary pressure," Schroeder told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
"We will certainly discuss it in Berlin. We will discuss a
procedure and perhaps a suggested candidate," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Schroeder admitted that a second informal summit might be
needed after Berlin to finalise the choice of a new president for
the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
The German Chancellor said Santer's successor would have to
possess political experience, economic knowledge, administrative
experience and absolute integrity.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Blair confirmed that the two heads of
government discussed the names of possible successors to Santer
but declined to give details.
</P>
<P>
But he said the new candidate would ideally serve out the
remainder of Santer's term and then be reappointed for a further
five years.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder arrived London Tuesday afternoon in his rush visit to
EU capitals to prepare for the Berlin meeting. 
</P>
