<HEADLINE> Economic Collapse Is Romania's Main Risk: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The main risk Romania faced
with nowadays is the collapse of the national economy, rather than
a foreign military invasion, Romanian President Emil
Constantinescu stressed here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The President made the remark in an address to the opening
session of a scientific conference on the country's national
interest and the security policy.
</P>
<P>
"At this moment, the danger of a military confrontation is
dwarfed by the threat of being defeated economically," he said,
adding that the corruption, the secondary financial markets, the
organized crime and the terrorism are also among the true risks
and contemporary threats posed on the national security.
</P>
<P>
"Many time from now, the big perils will relate to the
off-balanced financial-banking institutions and social relations,
the rate of the corruption and the organized crime," he said.
</P>
<P>
After 1990, Romania was destitute of any collective security
arrangement. A reason why it has been and it still is imperative
that Romania should become a NATO member, he said.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that the Romanian society does not see the
adherence to the NATO chiefly as a protection against some threat,
but as the regaining of an identity deprived for some good
decades. "The NATO does not account for a shelter to us, but for a
community of values," Constantinescu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
