<HEADLINE> Greenspan: U.S. Farming Benefits When World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. farming as a whole
appears well-positioned to benefit when Asian and other economies
around the world begin to recover, though farmers are suffering
from sharply falling prices for their products, Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Farmers, rather than sharing in the general prosperity, have
been experiencing disappointing exports and sharply falling
prices" during "what presumably is a transitory period of
softness," Greenspan said in a speech prepared for delivery to the
Independent Bankers Association of America in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
He said prices received by farmers are down 5 percent from a
year ago and prices for corn, soybeans, wheat and hogs have hit
levels unseen in years, principally blaming the worldwide
financial crisis that began in Asia in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Falling shipments to the Asian countries accounted for more
than 80 percent of the drop in the value of farm exports over the
past two years," he said, adding that shipments to Russia and
South America also have been affected.
</P>
<P>
The strong domestic economy hasn't made up for the loss of
exports, because "consumers, especially in affluent economies, do
not boost spending on food to nearly the same degree that their
incomes rise," he said amid some upbeat economic signs, including
the Dow Jones industrial average cracking the 10,000 barrier for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly our farm sector stands to gain, perhaps appreciably,
when more favorable economic conditions finally emerge" around the
world, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, farmers have responded "by reducing the costs of
production to the bare bone." And they've been helped by falling
prices for gasoline, diesel fuel and fertilizer, which helped
produce a 3 percent drop in prices farmers pay for goods, and by
past technological innovations that have made farmers more
efficient, and by increased government support payments.
</P>
<P>
"The weakening of farm markets, while pressuring farm income
and wealth, has not had effects as dramatic as the declines in
market prices might seem to have implied," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Despite heightened anxieties about how long the present
slack conditions in farm markets might persist, both farmers and
lenders appear to retain a fair degree of optimism about the
longer-run prospects for the sector," he said. "However, the
near-term may be challenging." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990317.0362 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Finances Container Transport Project in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved
Tuesday a loan of 71 million U.S. dollars for China's container
transport project, which will facilitate the inland movement of
seaborne containers from gateway ports to inland cities.
</P>
<P>
This project will help alleviate infrastructure bottlenecks in
China by developing an inland distribution system for seaborne
containers and improving service quality of the container inland
distribution market, the bank said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The project was designed to introduce effective competition in
container distribution markets by instituting intra-port
competition in Tianjin Port and enabling newly-created inland
container depot operators to offer alternative service options to
compete with large state-owned freight forwarders, according to
the bank.
</P>
<P>
It was also designed to advance enterprise reform through
facilitating project entities to transform themselves into
commercially-oriented enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The project will benefit, primarily, project provinces,
including land-locked provinces such as Inner Mongolia. These
beneficiaries will have better and more reliable access to foreign
markets. The establishment of shipping links to seaports will also
increase the attractiveness of these provinces as potential sites
for foreign direct investments.
</P>
<P>
Another group of beneficiaries will be foreign shipping lines
and freight forwarders as the policy reforms will contribute to
the creation of a more competitive business environment in China's
transportation sector.
</P>
<P>
The loan is at the World Bank's standard interest rate for
LIBOR-based U.S. dollar single-currency loans, with a maturity of
20 years, including a five-year grace period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
