<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mowlam Calls Killed Lawyer "Brave Woman" for Ulster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Northern Ireland
secretary on Tuesday called Rosemary Nelson, a Roman Catholic
lawyer killed by a car bomb on Monday in Northern Ireland, "a
brave woman" for a peaceful settlement of that violence-ridden
province.
</P>
<P>
She was "a brave woman who stood up for what she believed in
and carried those beliefs through into her work," Mo Mowlam said
in a speech when she came to the United States to accept an award
from the New England Global Citizens' Circle.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam said the killers of lawyer Nelson intended to destroy
the peace process in Northern Ireland. "They will not succeed,"
she said. An outlaw pro-British group, the Red Hand Defenders,
claimed responsibility for the killing, which sent shock waves
through the province.
</P>
<P>
Irish politics has moved to Washington in readiness for a
White House bash on St Patrick's Day and several of the key
players are already in Washington for politicking and
socializing -- part of an annual ritual that has expanded under
U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
By the time of the White House and Irish embassy St Patrick's
Day receptions on Wednesday, Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern,
Mo Mowlam, the British Northern Ireland secretary, Protestant leader
of Ulster Unionist Party and first minister-designate of the new
executive David Trimble and Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams would all
be in the U.S. capital.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the gathering is to try to break the deadlock in
Northern Ireland. But analysts here say it looks unlikely for
that as Protestant parties resist the province's absorption into
Ireland while Republicans demand an end to British rule in
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
And the Irish Republican Army refuses to begin disarming,
which has thus prevented its political wing, Sinn Fein, from
taking part in a power-sharing executive to run the province.
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt we are within a hair's breadth of a
settlement and it would be a tragedy if what we have is thrown
away in the next three weeks," Mowlam told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Trimble and Adams are expected to meet in Washington on
Wednesday morning. And there also will be a brief session between
the Northern Ireland politicians and Clinton. But diplomats did
not expect substantive negotiations at that meeting or that brief
session. They hoped U.S pressure might spur the parties toward
compromise and to find new ideas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
