<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Mulls Resumption of Financial Assistance for Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) announced Tuesday that its management has decided to
propose to the executive board to resume financial assistance for
Ukraine as the government has made progress in the fiscal and
structural areas.
</P>
<P>
A board meeting will be scheduled before the end of March to
consider this issue, the IMF said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The IMF approved last September a three-year extended
arrangement for Ukraine, equivalent to 2.25 billion U.S. dollars,
to support the government's 1998-2001 economic program. Of the
total, 300 million dollars has already been disbursed.
</P>
<P>
"Further disbursements were postponed because cash revenues
fell short of expectations, fiscal prospects for 1999 remained
unclear, and some structural reforms were behind schedule," the
IMF said.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the Ukrainian government has embarked upon a major
fiscal adjustment effort, aimed at reducing the overall cash
deficit from the equivalent of 2.7 percent of the gross domestic
product in 1998 to 1 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
As a result, cash revenue performance and expenditure controls
have improved and expenditures have been maintained within the
government's targets, the IMF said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
