<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets End On Mixed Mood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Europe's main stock markets had a
mixed day, although the shocking mass resignation of the European
Union executive body appears to have played little part.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 finished flat after modest mid-session gains
were wiped out by Wall Street's rapid retreat from record highs of
10001.78.
</P>
<P>
The index closed down 4.9 points at 6201.9, having peaked at
6269.6 in early trade.
</P>
<P>
U.S. movements were the controlling factor in a rather subdued
London market, said a chief dealer at a European bank.
</P>
<P>
"The Dow Jones may well set another record later in the
session, but the fact that it only spent a minute or so above
10000 took the steam out of the FTSE," he said.
</P>
<P>
German shares ended higher but failed to gain momentum from
Wall Street's early gains. The Xetra DAX index rose 47.70 points,
or 1 percent, to 5090.93.
</P>
<P>
Trader said the German market did not react to the Dow Jones
climbing briefly above 10000 points given last week's sharp gains.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC 40 index was boosted by a rally in banking
shares, which saw the blue-chip index move into the black in
afternoon trading to close just over 1 point higher at 4186.35.
</P>
