<HEADLINE> U.S. Says DPRK Agrees to Access to Kumchang-ri Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States announced
Tuesday that the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) had
agreed to allow access to an underground site which Washington
suspected was part of a nuclear project.
</P>
<P>
"An agreement has been struck in New York with the North
Koreans on access to the suspect underground site at Kumchang-ri,"
State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said the agreement would allow an unlimited number of visits
to the entire site, with the first visit to take place in May this
year.
</P>
<P>
He added that the second visit could take place in May 2000 and
that the visits would "enable us to confirm and monitor current
and future use of the suspect site."
</P>
<P>
Rubin said Washington did not agree to DPRK demands for
compensation for the access, but that it agreed to take part in a
bilateral agricultural scheme to improve potato production.
</P>
<P>
He said the bilateral agricultural scheme was a "very modest
potato project," which would be carried out by a private voluntary
organization. He added that it was the type of project Washington
had always envisaged under a 1994 bilateral agreement.
</P>
<P>
He said there would be a further round of talks between the two
countries on U.S. concerns over the DPRK's missile production and
sales in Pyongyang on March 29.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on Kumchang-ri, reached in New York and approved
by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, followed four rounds of
talks between U.S. and DPRK officials.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said there would be a further round of talks on March 29
between the two countries on what U.S. alleged was the DPRK's
missile production and sale.
</P>
<P>
last Friday, Pyongyang accused Washington of trying to press
for military dominance of Asia.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. is mistaken if it thinks that it can `check' the DPRK
missile development through `cooperation' with other countries,
and it should not dream that kind of dream," a Foreign Ministry
spokesman said in a report carried by the Korean Central News
Agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
