<HEADLINE> UN Borrows Less From Peacekeeping Funds to Cover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Addressing the Fifth Committee (Administration and Budget),
U.N. Under-Secretary-General for Management Joseph Connor said
those changes were due mainly to increased payments by the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Connor said While the country had contributed an amount
exceeding its assessed contribution for 1998, the amount it still
owed represented 76 percent of all unpaid regular budget
assessments at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the level of unpaid regular budget assessments was
decreasing substantially, said Connor, adding in 1995, unpaid regular
budget assessments have been 564 million U.S. dollars while at
the end of 1998, they came to 417 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The deficit in the regular budget cash was down, too, and at
the end of 1995, the regular budget cash position had been
negative 195 million dollars, but at the end of 1998, the
deficit was 40 million dollars, Connor said.
</P>
<P>
"We have no capital, we have no reserves, we borrow from
some Member States to make up for the income we do not get from
other Member States," Connor said.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations owed Member States 872 million U.S. dollars
for troops and contingent-owned equipment at the end of 1998 --
virtually the same as 1997 and 1996. Without significant payment
of arrears, that debt would remain intractable," he added.
</P>
