<HEADLINE> Death Toll in U.S. Train Accident Rises to 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- At least 13 people were killed
and five others were missing and feared dead in Monday's train
derailment at a crossing in Illinois State of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Rescue crews were still combing through a twisted, charred rail
car Tuesday, with hopes fading of finding survivors after a train
struck a truck and derailed, said reports reaching here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 people were reportedly injured in the accident.
</P>
<P>
"To find survivors in the wreckage would be pretty unlikely,"
Bourbonnais Fire Chief Mike Harshbarger said.
</P>
<P>
The train, bound from Chicago to New Orleans, careened off the
tracks shortly after 9:30 p.m. Monday (local time) when it slammed
into a semitrailer loaded with heavy steel bars at a crossing 90
kilometers south of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
All of the dead were aboard one sleeper car near the front of
the train. As the impact sent engines and cars flying, it was
pierced by one of the engines and then set afire by leaking diesel
fuel.
</P>
<P>
Rescue workers were digging by hand through debris in that car
Tuesday morning, Harshbarger said. The double-deck sleeper car was
broken in the middle, and much of it had been damaged by fire.
</P>
<P>
In all, local officials said, there were 196 regular
passengers, 18 crew members on duty and two off-duty employees
aboard the train, for a total of 216.
</P>
<P>
The number of dead, accounted-for and unaccounted-for given
earlier by authorities at the scene, totaled 214. There was no
immediate explanation for the discrepancy, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Some 100 were injured enough to be taken to hospitals. At least
11 were listed in critical condition Tuesday and 19 were in serious
condition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
