<HEADLINE> U.S. Calls Iraq's flight of Pilgrims "Cynical Ploy" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Tuesday
called Iraqi pilgrim flight to Saudi Arabia "cynical ploy" but
assured pilgrims that they would not be the target of the
Western patrolling planes over no-fly zones.
</P>
<P>
An Iraqi plane carrying 110 muslim pilgrims landed in the
western Saudi city of Jeddah on Tuesday in defiance of a U.N.
air embargo and of the U.S.-British-imposed no-fly zones which Iraq
has denounced since last December as flagrant encroachment of
its sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
But State Department spokesman James Rubin said the flight
violated U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"The bottom line here is Saddam Hussein has found another
cynical ploy and tried to exploit the hajj for his own purposes.
And all he's done is harm himself further internationally by
this violation of international sanctions," he said.
</P>
<P>
"However, Iraqi pilgrims are not a target" of U.S. and
British warplanes patrolling the no-fly zones, Rubin added. "On
the contrary, the no-fly zones that we established were to
protect the Iraqi people from their own government's repression,
and so we will not take any action that would put innocent Iraqi
pilgrims in danger."
</P>
<P>
Iraq, with a population of more than 20 million, can send up
to 22,000 pilgrims to Mecca under a quota system which limits
the number of Muslims who can attend from each country. Nearly
2,000 Iraqis arrived in the kingdom by land on Monday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
