<HEADLINE> Guinean Troops Engage S. Leonean Rebels in Heavy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Guinean troops of the west
African peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG engaged the rebels in
Sierra Leone in heavy fighting on Monday and Tuesday in the border
town of Kambia, a report reaching here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
An ECOMOG officer told reporters in Sierra Leonean capital
Freetown that the rebels Monday attacked Kambia on the border
between Guinea and Sierra Leone, and the heavy fighting continued
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted military sources as saying that thousands of
more troops were arriving from Guinea to shore up border defenses
following the attacks on Kambia launched by the Sierra Leonean
rebels.
</P>
<P>
Guinean forces at the weekend launched a major counter-attack,
including air strikes, against the rebels controlling much of
Sierra Leone's western border areas.
</P>
<P>
Aid workers said Guinean troops had pushed back the rebels,
who attacked the town of Pamalap in Guinea, back toward Kambia.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have suffered heavy casualties in the fighting
around Kambia with many bodies lying on the outskirts of the town,
aid workers were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian-led ECOMOG said Guinean troops are holding their
ground against the rebels in Kambia. However, travellers from the
area said the insurgents held large parts of the town. 
