<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Epidemic Claims 10 Victims in Netherlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- An epidemic, Legionnaires'
disease, at a Dutch flower show has killed 10 persons so far,
Dutch news media reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The bacterial infection was traced to a flower show in
Bovenkarpsel, 40 miles north of Amsterdam. Last month, some 80,000
people visited the weeklong Westfriese Flora show. Now the Dutch
government is trying to trace visitors of the show and determine
the exact source of the bacteria.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the bacteria stemmed from a fountain which
served as a centerpiece of exhibits. Usually, several national
flower shows are held throughout the western Netherlands each
Spring, when the 6 billion U.S.-dollar annual Dutch cut flower and
bulb industry shows off its wares.
</P>
<P>
The government confirmed on Monday that only five deaths were
due to Legionnaires' disease, although four others who had visited
the show since have died. Over 40 people were believed to have
been infected with the pneumonia-like illness.
</P>
<P>
Legionnaires' disease was first discovered after an outbreak at
a 1976 convention of the American Legion in Pennsylvania. The
bacteria that are believed to cause the illness are found in soil
and grow in air-conditioning ducts, storage tanks and rivers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
